,Recommended,248820,28729445,"Posted: 27 December, 2016",all,Black Puppet,"Disclaimer: Not everything in this Review is said on a serious note. Some things are jokes and I hope these are obvious enough.Risk of Rain fails for me as a actual Rougelike. Not that it cannot be classified as one, but the feeling overall just does not fit. If you are here and expect a game that is fast and deadly, dont buy this game. This game relies purely on you, how you react ingame and how fast you can spam the jump button.Risk of Rain, is a platformer based on the roguelike concept. Your main task is to find a teleporter to reach the next world. And this task continues in said world, until you reach the end. In these worlds themself you will have to fight aliens that teleport in, sent in by the villain (or at the very least that is my theory as to how they get there).  These aliens then drop experience and currency. Currency which you can use on the various crates and shrines. Even random cryostasis chambers are there to provide you with items, should you have the currency for it. And if you should find a broken drone, it can be repaired with your currency just as well.But of course that is not all to the game. The crates, shrines and stasischambers contain items that, similar to ""The Binding of Isaac"" give you passiv and active abilities. Some allow you to gain health while damaging your enemies. Others  will make your overall health grow as you kill. Then again another ability grants you a double jump. And here comes the best about this: The abilities can stack when you find the same item you carry with you. A double jump transforms into a triple jump. You gain more health when you damage enemies. You get more max health when you kill. But of course, these are just the buffs. There are items you can use activly in combat. One of my personal favorites is the saw-blade. It does a massive amount of damage and can kill entire lines of enemies in one shot, in the earlier stages of the game.But now the game gets hard. Actually, it is hard from the get go. You look at the little bar on the top right and you see your impending doom slowly but surely rising to the top. Why? Because this game does it differently to others. Of course, you can choose between easy, medium and hard. But these only depict as to how hard the enemies are to kill and how many of them will spawn (and how fast they spawn). And this only gets worse the longer you play. As the longer you play, the difficulty rises. It begins with a stroll in the park and ends up in hell. And there is no way to avoid it, unless you do a speedrun of the game. Which is also not that easy as the teleporter is randomly generated on the pre-set worlds. Knowing how the world looks may help, but not knowing where the teleporter is, does not. And in the end it is a literally a maze where one turn can let you end up in a place that throws you out and you need to continue to search for the right path all over again.And as if it wasnt enough already that the game gets harder by the minute, that the landscape is kind of like a maze and that the teleporter spawns randomly, there are bosses as well. And they are not easy to kill. They can move and attack, just like the regular enemies can. Some are easy to cheesy (or in other words; Some cant get up a ledge and can be killed from above without being able to attack you.) and others will simply fly towards you to get the kill. Others have an AOE to make sure that you are not safe on that elevated platform of yours and others again will be able to teleport towards you to kill you right quick.But if you have done it all, gotten through all the teleporters, you will end up in the main ship. The one you were dropped off of in a capsule. And here is the main villain as well. But how do you reach him? Do the same thing you did before, but this time a bit different. Instead of finding the teleporter, you need to find the keypads infront of the doors. This will then again spawn in a bunch of enemies and at this point in time, surely a few bosses as well. And if you made it through all of it: The grand finale awaits.- Authors Note -Why did I say that this game fails as a Roguelike for me even if it can be classified as one?I experienced Roguelike games, and love them dearly. But one aspect was very important every time. And that little aspect is: You are never safe. But of course this is way to broad so let me explain:In the very flagships of Roguelike, which are ""The Binding of Isaac"": ""Enter the Gungeon"" and ""Nuclear Throne"", you could die as quick as you began to play the game, if you were not carefull enough. Die and lose it all, at any given point in time. The gameplay was quick, had you on your toes at all times possible and killed you as fast as it could. One of the most important things was that it didnt, unless you had found an ability or a health pack, give you any health back. A little detail that makes the games much harder and challenging.But in Risk of Rain this does not stand true. The very first thing that makes a roguelike, a rougelike is that you are never safe unless you cleared out the room or floor. In Risk of Rain however you can activate the teleporter, let the enemies spawn until its done and if you feel overwhelmed you can rope up and take a break and wait until your health returns to charge right back into battle.And that is what bores me about this game. I played all three of the mentioned Roguelikes and I have been frustrated. The more I played them, the more I raged. The more I failed, the more I wanted to wish hell and death on the devs for creating this piece of garbage. But after I calmed down I loved every second of what I experienced it. I guess I am a gaming masochist but still. And that is something, this game does not provide.This game is a stroll in the park no matter how high your difficulty is. You can get out of every situation with literally every character. The first one is actually the easiest. A dodgeroll helps you get out of the situation with immunity frames, you go up the rope and Boom: You are safe. But in a true Roguelike, you are never safe. You are never free from simply dodging damage unless it has to do with you actually dodging the damage. Which is absolutely possible in a 2D topdown roguelike. But not in 2D platformer roguelike. Only if you actually spam jump or dodgeroll, you can get out with no damage at all.So, do I think that Risk of Rain is a good game?- YesDo I think that Risk of Rain is a good Roguelike?- NoShould you buy it?- Yes"
