,Recommended,248820,7893074,"Posted: 3 December, 2013",all,Empty,"This game offers a nice combination of retro platformer and roguelike, with a touch of modern video games (particularly mobas) I rate it 8/10From an artstyle perspective, they nail it perfectly. The pixel art in the game is beautiful, detailed and not just thrown in there to give it the classic indie platformer artstyle, you can see that all the art has had lots of work go into it, rather than a lot of games that go with very simplistic shapes and objects and then pixelate them to cover the gap in the art skills of the team.The soundscape works amazingly with the game, you truly feel like you're exploring a strange planet where little makes sense and even less isn't trying to kill you.Finally, the gameplay. While simple and to some degree repetitive (jump, shoot, kite, repeat) it keeps it fresh with loads of different classes, all with very different playstyles. The platforming is tight, the combat is very fun and highly enjoyable, and the randomised mechanics improve the games longevity significantly. In addition, coop play is extremely fun, and probably the biggest draw of the game.The game does lose points for the random factor though, levels, enemy 'mutators' and the item drops are randomly generated each game, but the bosses are always usually the same and the levels are very samey. This doesn't detract severely, but I feel after 2 or 3 runs, you've seen everything the game has to offer, a lot of games suffer this and it's not always an issue (e.g. Killing Floor) but I feel that the game runs out of surprises fairly quickly.The one exception is the items, the items are the best part of the game by far, nearly all of them are unique and most of them are thoroughly enjoyable. The background lore of each item is interesting (and at times hilarious) and the craziness of certain item combos gets you hooked and wanting more. I think they did an amazing job on the item design and the pacing of how they are deployed to the player (you unlock items through repeated play throughs, granting them as potential drops for next game)Overall, RoR is an excellent game, it has some small flaws, but in general the gameplay is excellent and the art and sound direction are beautiful. I'm hard pressed to find many indie games that compare to it's level of polish. I eagerly await future updates to the game with even more content and features!"
