,Recommended,248820,9227325,"Posted: 22 February, 2014",all,Jungle Rot the Pyronaut,"Ignore what Steam says, I've been playing the game for well over 60 hours.If you want a challenge, Risk of Rain does not disappoint. Although the concept of getting to the teleporter at the end of each level is simple, and there are only 6 levels in any single playthrough, it just doesn't get old. Ever. After dying 2-3 times I looked up at the clock and an hour and a half had passed. The incredibly addicting gameplay and a near endless amount of items give this game a very similar feel to The Binding of Issac.It's hard, but not unfair.Difficult, but rewarding.Sometimes makes you rage and throw your computer, then pick it back up again and give it 'one more go'.There are tons of unlockables and achivements to test your skill. Beating them unlocks more items and characters as to help you make it further in your next run. Like I said, there are only 6 levels in any one playthrough, but the first four can be switched at random, leading to a total of 10 areas and more to explore. Different stages spawn different enemies, and your teleporter, chests, items, and idols won't be in the same place during your next run. Heck, the same bosses won't even show up. I'd been playing the game for 2 days and found a boss I'd never seen before. Beating the game requires both skill and luck to get the right items. And since no two playthroughs will ever be the same, you can't just expect to get the items you've been hoping for, but you make what you get work.If you like tough games, lots of variety, and simple gameplay that just doesn't get old; Buy Risk of Rain.Also, I can honestly say this game has one of the most fun and just downright enjoyable (yet difficult) final bosses I've seen in a game, which has also become a personal favorite of mine.There isn't much that this game does wrong. 9/10"
