,Recommended,248820,7967186,"Posted: 8 December, 2013",all,LukteDukte,"Risk of Rain is both unique and the same as any other game with Permadeath. What makes a game different if it's the same game but unique at the same time? Gameplay and the way you change it and interact with it, just a bit. Music, sound and art style counts to.Most games (But not all games) with Permadeath has a recurring Dungeon Crawler theme, go in with nothing, explore, grab the loot and kill enemies to become stronger to reach the goal. Now ""Reach the goal"" can change dramatically how the gameplay difficulty is. Make the goal short makes the gameplay harder and make the goal longer makes the gameplay easier but makes you on edge not to die, like Diablo III or Path of Exile. There is also games with no clear goal(Minecraft and Terraria) that makes the gameplay the same even if permadeath is on, It only makes you on edge when you play.Risk of Rain uses the short goal way(short goal, harder gameplay) but it change the gameplay difficulty to a more timely manner, Time = Difficult. The longer you play the harder the game is. Suddenly the pattern is change, short goal with progressive(time) difficulty. With that pattern and the easy to play controls and the fun easy gameplay becomes much much enjoyable. It's like surfing, riding the difficulty and feel that you can do enything, as long your on the surfing board.I highly recommend you buy it and play it with a friend. It's one of those games that I can play again and again without feeling bored of it's mechanics. A fun unique game."
,Recommended,248820,8463907,"Posted: 31 December, 2013",all,Veckz,"A solid (and nicely priced) game, Risk of Rain is fun and the perfect introduction for newbies into the genre of games with roguelike elements. It's easy to jump into, controls are simple, lots of hidden unlockables for replayability, and the gameplay is straightforward. The straightforward gameplay has its pro's and con's. Personally, I think that it limits the game somewhat, because it does seem more repetitive than say, Binding of Isaac or Spelunky. The randomized levels don't make much of an impact here than it does in Spelunky. And the loose-nature of RPG-styled combat makes battles less intense compared to Binding of Isaac. But the lack of complexity, IMO, is what makes multiplayer possible and enjoyable. Now... if only there was matchmaking for the online."
