,Recommended,248820,9241062,"Posted: 23 February, 2014",all,Notesurfer,"Risk of Rain has large pool of potential, but ultimately it dries up too quickly. The gritty pixelated visual style conveys perfectly the sense of almost-overwhelming struggle as you grind your way through hordes of monsters to escape the planet. The music is epic, blood-pumping, and catchy, imbuing the player with a sense of awe and urgency. Unfortunately, the level generation features only a handful of different layouts per zone, which makes each playthrough feel very much like the last. Varied enemies and classes break up the monotony very well, but, like playing with different action figures in the same sandbox, one begins to tire of the surroundings. The zoomed-out field of view and slow player movement give combat a sense of grandiosity and scale, but after a few hours of play that can easily transform into frustration of pace. Most characters and achievements can be unlocked on ""Drizzle"" (easy) difficulty, which de-incentivizes playing on the harder difficulties. The types of items you find can also make or break a run, meaning that later levels are often either tedious (as you slowly chip away at enemy health) or boring (as you steamroll over them).Risk of Rain is definitely a fun game, but for long-term enjoyment it stagnates as many small problems coagulate into a somewhat unrewarding experience. It is definitely recommended however, for its unique feel: the production is exemplary, with gameplay and atmosphere bound up seamlessly into one experiential package."
