,Recommended,248820,8755959,"Posted: 18 January, 2014",all,Astr00waldo,"Space. Ship. Containers (lots of them). A strange guy with a sword. Crash.That's what the intro of the game shows the player, right after launching it.Then the player goes through a poorly designed menu (It's simple, but it's strange and acts weirdly, for example, if you are in options and press ""Esc"", the window that was supposed to appear when you are in the middle of a match appears, instead of simply going a step back, like all other games in Earth), where he can choose from Solo match, multiplayer game, options, an item showcase (so you can see the description and a brief story behind everything you end up grabbing in the game), the Monster Log - which is pretty cool, showing you a description and field notes on the enemies you fight along the game, but of course, you need to kill a lot of them and be lucky enough so they drop a log first - and an achievements/challenges options which tells you quite a few things and gives you nice challenges. And yes, they're hard enough.Stepping away from the game menu, the player will find him/herself in a deserted planet controlling one from the 10 choosable characters - which you need to do certain things to unlock, you just start with the Commando - with a minimalistic user interface and will see only one written thing at the start: ""Find the teleporter"". By this point, the soundtrack kicks in and the game starts doing what it's supposed to do. You don't know where to go, you don't know what to do, but you know that you need to find the teleporter, and you must do it fast because there's a timer on the top right of the screen telling you the game difficulty. You don't know what that means, but you know that you don't want the time meter to fill.So you run through the map, discovering the amazingly beautiful pixellated world of Risk of Rain. Enemies start popping up from nowhere and you know that you need to kill them. You get experience, level up, get better damage and more health, you get coins which you can use to open chests, activate shrines, and get random items from a set that ranges from a rusty knife, which will give you a chance of bleeding on hit, to a health-leeching seed which gives you passive lifesteal. Most of the items are passive, but there are active items ranging from awesome to♥♥♥♥♥♥ And yes, this adds up to the fun.The gameplay is quite simple, your character has 4 abilities, each one with its cooldown (except the first one, which is your main attack), and you must use them to fight your way through each level until you are able to exit the strange planet you're in, killing hordes of strange and challenging monsters (including bosses). And the soundtrack always making that pixellated chaos even more badass.The game has minor flaws, for instance, the amazingly low number of different enemies. Yes, they're good, they'll give you hours of pain and you'll enjoy killing them, but sometimes you want something different, that's when I think the developers should give us an update or a DLC with new enemies and new levels. But that's minor, as I said before, there are even different ""tiers"" for enemies, so they'll sure give you some trouble and not get cheap.""Risk of Rain"" shows its glory to the player ever since their first playthrough. A painful run, of course, on a game in which you know nothing, but then the player ends up realizing how fun and how fast the time passed by while playing this little gem. It's a must-have for everyone who likes roguelike games, getting side-by-side with The Binding of Isaac in all its glory. 9/10"
