,Recommended,248820,30016432,Posted: 18 February,all,Hattori,"Risk of Rain is yet another roguelike where the main appeal is to unlock as many items you can and to see how long you can survive.And I would say it achieves those two aspects pretty well. It manages to differentiate itself from other similar games by how its gameplay mechanics work.While the overall aesthetic boils down to pretty much a 2d side scroller platformer, the combat takes its inspiration from MMORPGs, where you have to wait a few seconds before you can utilize a certain hability again. This creates a really great flow between how you deal with large numbers of enemies because at any point you have to take into consideration what attacks and habilities you can utilize.Each character you unlock is vastly different from the one you used before, and they all provide different strategies and ways of approaching the enemies.Another interesting mechanic is the difficulty. Time is always counting in Risk of Rain, and difficulty scales with it. The brilliance of the game however is that you cant simply rush to the end in an attempt to keep the difficulty low.Levels are huge and to beat them you must first find the teleporter to activate it and wait 90 seconds before you can use it, while having to fight an onslaught of enemies and a boss.Between that, you have to earn enough money by killing enemies so you can unlock treasure chests that earn you a wild variety of items that will stack up to turn you into a killing machine.Part of the fun of the game is to figure out what those items do so I wont spoil them, but the spectacle that they create as you manage to exterminate hundreds of enemies in a few shots is the highlight of the game.And its this balance that makes Risk of Rain so much fun. Should you just rush it to the end goal? Or should you waste some more time upgrading your stuff before moving on to a harder level?Risk of Rain contains some randomization as you would expect from the genre, but they are very lite, being pretty much just the order of pre-built levels, item placement, teleporter, enemies and bosses. Being that a big chunk of your time is spent exploring the level, its a good decision that they arent procedurally generated, so that way you can easily orientate yourself .""Game Feel"" is also on point, shooting enemies is incredibly satisfying and blowing 10 or 20 of them in on move never gets old.Risk of Rain however isnt what I would call perfect game design. The game has a weird case of ""dead air"" where you arent sure what to do. Let me explain:You start the level and your priorities are to find items to upgrade yourself. You need money for that, so you need to kill enemies. Enemies wont spawn until a few minutes into the level, and when they do it's in very short bursts. The best way to get money is to activate the teleporter and fight the army that ensues. But you arent prepared for that because you didnt get enough upgrades. So you wait for enemies to spawn while you explore the level in search of chests to get items. It creates a strange paradox where you are forced to wait for enemies in a game that is all about moving as fast as you can.This is the worst part of the game for me, it feels like an inbetween before the real fun of the game, especially since the levels are so big and your character moves so slowly.This doesnt make it a bad game, not at all, its just not very well designed, but luckily the good stuff about the game vastly makes up for this.Another thing I would say the game lacks is maybe quantity. Weird nitpick I know, but it really feels like the game would benefit from having more♥♥♥♥♥♥in it. Kinda like Binding of Isaac's numerous upgrades and expansions.Risk of Rain has a very short selection of levels and bosses, and enemies do become repetitive after a few hours, containing only slight variations of colour and health.Regardless, you should definitely play this game, the last level is just insane with the amount of enemies you have to deal with and the final boss is no pushover. The pixel art is gorgeous, the animations of enemies and your character are great and the soundtrack is phenomenal.All in all, I highly recommend Risk of Rain."
