,Recommended,248820,13482796,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,Drianko,"An awesome Rogue-Lite/Platformer made of 8-bit goodnessRisk of Rain has the potential to become one of your favorite games if you have the stomach for its challenging gameplay and incredible difficulty. This game has been one of the harder titles I've attempted to play in recent years, and the satisfaction of having completed even a marginally successful run is immense.Graphics: 9/10Pixel art is the oldest tool for 2d games, it's great and you can tell how much effort was put to it. RoR has some pretty damn good Pixel art, with great palette choices going from gloomy colors to vibrant ones. While the backgrounds are not the best, they do not bore and thanks to the variations on the maps and the random spawn system, this game is far from tedious. The enemies on this game is where the Graphics shine though, the designs are awesome and Bosses are quite memmorable.Sound: 10/10Beautiful chip tunes and synth notes with a dark mood that perfectly adorn the atmosphere of the game. It mix-matches different genres, including prog rock, metal, drum 'n' bass and industrial, giving it a great ""psychedelic trip"" feel that helps the player become immerse in this concept of exploring a vast and hostile strange planet.Playability: 9.5/10Controls are simple and responsive, in both, the keyboard and Joypad. And thanks to the multiple playable characters, you have a ton of strategies to tackle the game with. The difficulty on this game is... Let's just say it's not for the faint of heart, but it remains fair all in all. It is also part of the unique game mechanics that it offers, being that it get's more difficult as time passes, this is relevant because you can skip the last level and keep revisiting the previous ones to farm items and XP at the cost of a higher challenge and putting all your progress at risk.Replay Value: 10/10Tons of items and a dozen of playable charaters to unlock + An insane difficulty that will foil your plans, make this game replayable to the point of addiction."
