,Recommended,248820,10719961,"Posted: 23 June, 2014",all,Brekfast Cyborg,"If you're debating on whether or not to pick this game up, I can assuage those doubts of yours. Before buying this I spent at least 30 hours in the game going through levels over and over again, trying to unlock those last few items (and this was before artifacts were added).Risk of Rain is a skill based side-scrolling action game where your main objective is to find the teleporter in each level. Once the teleporter is found, however, a countdown starts where you must stay alive until it finishes, a task made all the more difficult due to the boss monster that spawns as soon as you activate the teleporter. The game falls into a good rhythm: find the teleporter, kill the boss/enemies, go to the next level. Of course there are mechanics that add a bit of complexity to it, such as the items that can be found for sale around the level, the ever increasing difficulty level, and the variety of levels. The game features permadeath, as no characters can keep their levels once dead. However, new items, characters, and artifacts can be unlocked for subsequent playthroughs through completing the game's challenges, which range from somewhat simple to, at times, ridiculous, and finding hidden items throughout the levels. It is in this way that Risk of Rain gives the player a feeling of progression even after the loss of all the avatar's levels after death.The items found in the game can be purchased by money dropped by defeated monsters. These items increase your survivability in a myriad of ways, but the downside is that there is no explanation of what the item does when you purchase it. Players who come across one of the game's ""Item Shops"" (which are really just three items next to each other, two of which will disappear when one of them is bought) will only have the small picture of the item to give them some clue as to what it does. While some might find it frustrating at first, I liked the fact that there is no explanation, as it immerses the player into the situation of their avatar, stumbling across some strange object in a foreign planet where nothing is familiar and hoping it helps them survive the hordes of ever-looming alien creatures. All the pictures of the items are clearly discernable, however, and on subsequent playthroughs of the game the player will become intimately familiar with the items.There are quite a few unlockable characters, and players will unlock some of them just by completing the levels in the game. A choice few, however, can be found in certain hidden spots throughout the levels. Each character has a different enough playstyle than the rest, and while some of the make the game a little too easy I believe that helps the new player learn the levels before going at another playthrough with a different character.While the player can spend as much time as they need to on a level, there is a downside to spending too much time in one place. In the top right the player can see what looks like a thermometer, which represents the current difficulty level in the game. Every few minutes the difficulty level goes up, which means that more monsters will spawn, more elite (tougher) monsters will spawn, and every item will be more expensive with each new difficulty level. While I'm not a fan of timers, this does add a new time management dimension to the experience. By not penalizing the player with death for taking more time than needed and instead increasing the difficulty, the game opens up new strategies for players to interact with the game. For example, some players spend as little time as possible on the first level, as this means the later levels will be a bit easier and (more importantly) items will be cheaper. However, some spend up to five minutes on this level, as they want to get all of the items on the level so they can be better equipped for the next levels. More monsters also means more experience and money, so if the player's skill level is high enough they can intentionally spend more time than needed in order to force more monsters to spawn and level up even more.The levels in the game are sprawling and visually attractive. Instead of forcing you to go to one level every playthrough, the game randomly picks from two levels. For example, for Level One there are two options (Worlds 1-1 and 1-2), for Level 2 there are also two options (2-1 and 2-2) and the same can be said for Level 3. Levels 4 and 5 are the same, however, but because of the variety in the first three levels it feels less grating on multiple playthroughs as the player does not know exactly what to expect.There are also collectables to get in the levels that randomly drop. One such collectable is a monster log, which has a low chance of dropping when you kill a certain monster. This collectable unlocks some art and a description of the monster in the main title screen. The more interesting collectibles (gameplay-wise at least) are the artifacts, which will randomly appear throughout the levels. On getting these artifacts, you are able to activate them on subsequent playthoughs to make the game even harder.Risk of Rain is an excellent game in all respects. The only flaws I can find in it are the soundtrack (which is good at times but not as great as others have told me it was) and the fact that getting online co-op to work is a chore (I mostly play single player though). The visual style is aesthetically pleasing (I especially liked the boss designs) and controls are tight and responsive. Definitely worth the money considering the time you can put into it."
