76561198026872065,Recommended,248820,17478248,"Posted: 10 August, 2015",all,DrVaughn,"Alright folks. This is an interesting one for me. Buckle up.Risk of Rain, as most of you are propably well aware, is a game that falls into the category of roguelike (or rather roguelites). You are, most of the time at least, supposed to die at some point. Although there is a clear end to a run. A run will take you on average something from 10 to 60 minutes, depending on your ability to survive. Each run is gonna be different, based on the following factors: Your starting character, the selection of levels you are gonna get, the equipment you'll receive and the bosses you encounter along the way. I say ""selection"" of levels, because in contrast to a lot of other roguelites there is no random level generator. The game has a set of different levels within a set of various settings. The selection and order of those will be random each playthrough though.Each character comes with different skills and attacks, which helps the replayability a ton. The characters feel unique and distinguished enough from each other, that you want to unlock them and try them and roll with them.Gotta push that in here: The way you unlock the characters is marvellous if you ask me and it reminds me of the times of old. Some characters you unlock through simple playthroughs, but others you unlock by literally finding them in a specific level and fighting them. Others you unlock by finding a set amount of items or doing some kind of challenge. The ways are unqiue and it made the game feel mysterious to me. Hidden characters could be anywhere at any time - and I adore this kind of design-choice!Anyway, although the characters feel different from each other, the development within a run seems very limited. As per genre your run and character will develop with the items you'll receive and most of the items don't really make you adjust your strategy all that much.You shoot missiles at times? Cool, keep holding the fire button as always and just enjoy the bonus.Got lifesteal? Same thing.More crits? No need to adjust - just enjoy.You get what I mean. But to be fair - there are active items which add to your strategic decisions and there are some passive items that will make you think.You drop a banner at leveling up, that increases your attack speed when near. Well, better stay here then.You do damage to enemies that come too close? Risky, but maybe I should use that.Still, often times to me it feels, that from stage 2 onwards you'll be doing the same routine for most of the remaining run - the most effective strategy based on your characters skillset. It's still fun and I adore the endgame (including the final boss), but I feel like there was more potential.I don't wanna elaborate to much on the presentation, because this kind of style is something you love or you hate. I love pixelart, I love the simplicity and the soundtrack to my ears is gorgeous. From a presentation standpoint I got nothing to complain about.Let's put this together and clear up why this game is a special one to me.The flaws of the game are obvious and I know which parts and designchoices I don't agree with, but I still keep coming back. Give it a month or two, but I'll be back - and I'll be enjoying it as much as I ever did. I get curious, I get excited, I get a bit frustrated at times. And although I unlocked most of the game - there is still this sense of mystery for me. There are still riddles within the levels of which I know (or seen parts of) but haven't solved yet. There are still characters I haven't quite mastered and items I haven't seen. I still feel this sense of complete accomplishment, everytime I beat the final boss. No matter how often I come back - the game, so far, did not get stale for me.There is just something in this game that caters to my gaming-needs in a special way. The genremix of platformer and roguelite, the fireworks on the screen, the art design, the difficulty. Something in between all those qualities just gets me everytime - and propably will as well in the far future."
