,Recommended,248820,13124682,"Posted: 28 November, 2014",all,sny,"Behind Risk of Rain's simple premise and oldschool graphics is an edge-of-your-seat exciting masterpiece in game design that's hard as nails to get the hang of, but thoroughly satisfying once you do. And then you try a different character and the cycle begins anew.The basic concept is simple: get strongerfasterthan your enemies do. This is easier said than done, of course - the levels, enemies and loot are randomized and there are numerous chance-based decisions and events at play, but after a few deaths you'll slowly learn how to ride the difficulty wave with your chosen character.The game challenges you to challenge yourself: you can only unlock some of the stronger items (that can give you an edge in subsequent games) by completing hard tasks on different levels or using different characters. Because of this system, striving for certain achievements - albeit still arbitrarily established by the developers - has tangible, noticable benefits on your progress. Plus, the excitement of unlocking something new to play with and the enjoyment you get when you complete the feat is much stronger.The fact that there is a very thin line between being overwhelmed easily and being an unstoppable killing machine makes the game all the more exhilarating to play - even when you're doing well, you know you can't slack or take your time, or the enemies will catch up to you in strength and/or numbers.The controls are fluid and the simplistic graphics help you make sense of the chaos that will inevitably ensue once you've progressed far enough. The music is indescribably brilliant and goes perfectly with the visuals and the action-packed nature of the game.If you can't take being given the short straw by the RNG gods from time to time, if you're frustrated when a game is punishingly difficult after an hour of play, if you can't stand looking at graphics that evoke those of games on Commodore 64, move along, this game is not for you. If these traits don't bother you, you'll get some of the most adrenaline-pumping and rewarding gameplay available in a non-PvP game, wishing other games were as brave with their learning curves as this."
