,Recommended,248820,16506649,"Posted: 18 June, 2015",all,wtf,"If you think Dark Souls is difficult, try RoR."
,Recommended,248820,15032919,"Posted: 24 March, 2015",all,Matty G,"Risk of Rain is a game somewhat comparable to The Binding of Isaac in that you collect mostly passive items and activated ones to kill things while finding your way to the next stage, and the only thing you can get out of a failed run are more unlocked items and characters you may have earned. It also features online co-op as well as local play.Without the use of the in-game artifacts you can discover during gameplay, the game feels slow as ♥♥♥♥ as you and your friends will most likely end up kiting enemies all the time. However, the Glass artifact makes the players' damage output actually tolerable and lowers starting health enough for a fair compromise, and therefore makes the game much more enjoyable by making both the player and every enemy able to die much faster.By default players have to improvise by finding randomized items because enemies get (slightly) tougher every passing minute on the game clock, and money found from containers and dead enemies is required to open chests containing these, though it may also be spent on reactivating any heal/attack drones around that might be of use or trying your luck at shrines. For such an important mechanic of the base game's gameplay, it is interesting thatthe use of artifacts can gut all of this out completely;Command allows players to cherrypick items they want (even supposedly locked items!), and chests/shrines/drones can be removed in favor for enemies having a chance of dropping items with Sacrifice, and Honor can force most enemies to spawn as Elites...that have a bigger chance of dropping items if a certain item is picked up. The result is that a large chunk of randomization can be exchanged for consistency if one so desires, with players spending less time finding items and rushing find the teleporter out.Perhaps the biggest problem I have is that the game certainly wasn't balanced around Glass, especially with Honor activated. This means the first two or so levels have a chance to spawn an elite version of a boss that now spews electricity, called the Overloading Magma Worm, which very easily insta-kills players using a character without any real means of dodging or negating the damage and thus quickly turns the run into a waste of time if they haven't found a good enough environment or ideal items to take them on with. It does not mean those characters are entirely useless, they just have bad odds very early on unless playing with friends that can take out the boss much faster. Thankfully, the odds for seeing a even more cruel boss that fires electricity orbs on the first few levels are lower.The game has considerable replay value, but there may not be enough variation for some. I can definitely recommend Risk of Rain to BoI fans and those who like games with similar gameplay structures."
