,Recommended,248820,25795025,"Posted: 1 October, 2016",all,Doppelganchor,"Risk of Rain is a wonderful roguelike platformer with so very much to offer. When it was released in 2013 I had no idea how many hours I'd eventually sink into this little gem with my friends, as well as on my own. My friends and I would get together every weekend and attempt to take on the challenge of ""Monsoon"" difficulty. We'd get further and further into each randomly selected level each time and fail. We'd all beaten Rainstorm together and individually, and Monsoon gave us a challenge we all found to be a driving force. We'd all regroup weekend after next talking about the characters we'd unlocked and how we got them, what achievements and items we'd unlocked, and our plans for our next Monsoon run. We'd share the loot from each level, sometimes we'd call every item first come first serve, but no matter how we played we always had a good time. We'd play late into the evenings, run to the nearest 24/7 grocery store for snacks in the middle of the night, and return to do it all over again until the sun rose. This game is among many other fond memories I have of gaming growing up. At this point, it may only be three years since we started playing, but so much can happen in three years time and it has felt like Risk of Rain has always been a game I could return to with or without friends. Singleplayer is even more of a challenge and I for one am always itching to see how far I can get through Monsoon on my own. I highly recommend this game to others who are in search of a game that's challenging, quirky, unforgiving, and extremely rewarding. Going through the bestiary entries and item descriptions in the menu reminds me of how much I've put into the game and how many memories it gave me in return (not to mention the super rad item drops that come with unlocking new items and use-items). The lore is absolutely enticing and the longer you play the more you're immersed in the world, as well as with your character. Good luck, bring an umbrella."
,Recommended,248820,21742875,"Posted: 9 March, 2016",all,Goat Ghost,"This game starts off simple and easy. You do well, killing monsters as you jump above them, shooting/slashing/bombing them into a new level of hell. The time ticks on, you think, nay, believe that you are doing well. The big boss comes after the first level. You leveled up, you're decked out with new gear. You feel invulnerable.The boss crashes into the soft ground, body parts everywhere. You are triumphant. You move on to the next level. Yes.Then it starts to go to hell. You explored to long, you took to long to find the portal to get to the next level, you didn't get the right gear. Looking at the timer, it has changed.Everything starts to change, things are faster. More monsters pop into existence, they are bigger, badder, hungrier for your naive flesh. Bodies piling, you are struggling to keep up against the onslaught. Soon you're no longer shooting, you are jumping, running.You see the portal, activate it, then hold your breath for a minute and a half. Then you only hear the sound of a few dozen monsters coming down on you.You died.You start the game again. It's simple and easy...."
