,Recommended,248820,9925299,"Posted: 24 April, 2014",all,TBBle,"For something to play when you don't want to dedicate an afternoon to something, this is spot-on. You jump in, round around, shoot things and die. A bit like Rouge Legacy with guns and no RPG elements.And like Rogue Legacy, I can enjoy it even though I'm apparently terrible at it. There's a screen shot up there with 92 minutes on it, my personal best is probably less than 15 minutes due to very very lucky item drops making me nigh-unkillable. (""nigh-"" being the operative word there. There's always a way...)But that's okay. Death is expected, and it's very easy to just hit ""play again"" and charge straight back in.The only downside is lack of Steam Cloud support, so I can't have this installed everywhere for a five-minute blasting-things fest as the whim takes me."
76561197980503707,Recommended,248820,12331303,"Posted: 2 October, 2014",all,Zaimad,"Risk of Rain, where to even begin...? The ship you were on was damaged greatly by an unknown assailant and you crash-landed on a planet with lots of incredibly very hostile lifeforms... and you got stranded incredibly far from the wreck. Luckily, the ship you were on was a cargo ship: everything in it was ""unfortunately"" also stranded, and you can bet your life on the fact that those now-misplaced goods will be the most valuable things you'll need in order to attempt to leave the planet.Risk of Rain (RoR from now on) features preset stages with some randomization, where monsters litterally pop from the ground every now and then, boxes have to be properly paid for (with the spoils of popping monsters) in order to get your hands on their sweet contents and portals have to be found in order to traverse the hostile world as you try to get back to your damaged ship. But be ready: once you activate a portal and wait for it to ""charge up"", a powerful monster boss appears. After a set amount of time charging the portal, no more monsters appear and you must eliminate all the threats remaining in order to move on with your quest for safety.In RoR you can have up to 10 different character choices when you start the game. The default and starting one, the Commando, is pretty well balanced and intersting to play, but the other 9 are more specific in their gameplay as to what you should be doing and what you'd favour getting boosted by the various items you can find. Some are more challenging to play with than others, most definitely, and some are much harder to unlock than others. Also to keep in mind is the fact that you can collect throughout the different stages game-changing artefacts that WILL make or break the experience of some of the characters.I can confidently say that I had the least fun time of my life playing the Enforcer, a human-riots-specialized shield-wall with some area-of-effect options and side-defined damage mitigation skill, and loved playing the Mercenary, a ninja-like sword-wielding blur of speed that can avoid damage with two of its skills. Noteworthy mentions are the easy-mode Engineer, the run-and-gun Huntress and the only-with-item-choosing-artefact Sniper that can litterally one-shot the final boss (or make you run into a bug where you make the final boss nigh-invulnerable, and doing 2 damage per attack for more than 15k hp can take well over 30 minutes with the wrong items). Acrid and H4NDY (or with an A, don't remember) are also interesting in their own way, and the Miner is incredibly complex in terms of mobility and self-preservation. And there's also the Bandit, which feels a little underwhelming if you get it after you unlock the Huntress; just saying.The items you can find on your journey to the ship are also very much unique in their functions, or in certain cases there's a relation between a more common white item and a not-as-common green one (such as critical hit chance), but each and every item has a purpose and an ideal synergetic relation to each of the characters (or a broad spectrum of characters, such as happens with Paul's Goat's Leg, which increases move speed: everyone should have it). Items' effects stack, some with better results than others (you can't have more than 100% chance of a critical hit, for example), and some items are not really worth stacking unless you have no choice on the matter (I'm looking at you, Golden Gun). Bosses also drop unique items on rare occasion that might be just the extra edge you needed to stay alive or kill something better. And every enemy type, all the bosses included, have a chance to drop a monster log that will let you get some insight as to the world you've crash-landed on... and perhaps even the reason behind the attack on the ship, spoilers which I won't reveal.Naturally, RoR has a major flaw: it's inherent quality is that you will benefit the most of it the more you play it and replay it, but at some point you will have unlocked everything and found out the strategy that best fits you or your playstyle with whichever character you chose. And by that point, you will have seen pretty much all that the game has to offer, barring unlockables that you might not even need or will end up not really picking up once unlocked. You'll still have fun playing the game, but you will feel like you need to forget about it for a while to make it worth booting it up again; this is especially true once you reach a point where you've been alive for over 2 hours stacking items to the point of glitchyness and automatic downscaling of settings just to let the game run properly... Fun fact: I once became so overpowered that I just left my character unattended on a level and had a heavy lunch, only to find out an hour later that I was not only still alive but with tons of new crap uncollected to make me even more overpowered. Of course, I went for the final boss afterwards, since I had ""taken the♥♥♥♥♥♥out of it"" and any sense of challenge with it.You may be pleased to know the game has online multiplayer, as well as local multiplayer, and you can choose repeated characters (which is a good thing, considering a group of 4 people playing without anything unlocked would render the option moot). Playing online with your friends is fun, but one thing that happened significantly often with even someone on the same LAN as myself was a slight desynchronization of the game, including enemies that existed for one of us and not the other and, most annoyingly, the position or even the existence of items. This is more frequent the more items you start stacking up, of course, since more things have to be synchronized to begin with, and especially with area-calculated things happening (such as high amounts of Barbed Wire). In short, online is FUN, but only if you accept that really bad/annoying things may happen as part of the experience.I do have to say that there are some reallyannoyingbugs. I, for one, hate with a passion just how unclickable the difficulty can get to be with overlapping texts and whatnot. There should also be a back button on the multiplayer screen, forcing you to instead use the escape-key menu, or at the very least a ""no, wait, I've selected a character but I really changed my mind and want to select another one"" button in that menu. Textboxes may and will innevitably get stuck, be it trying to read how a skill is scaling or hovering some other annoying thing while in-game. And I find it so anti-climatic, the lines that the final boss spews, for their oh-so-annoyingly consistent typo all across the game (can't remember which it is, but I know it also happens on the descriptions and flavour texts of some of the items, since it is actually an English rule that is being broken); I can say that it's one of the reasons that every time I clear the game again I feel like I need to cool down and not play it for another week.Having mentioned all the relevant things, how much do I recommend it?Very much, that's for sure. RoR certainly feels unique enough in the sense that I know no other game that makes me feel good about commiting genocide on some lizard people, allows me to essentially fly with a continuously executed jump-slash as a ninja and invariably laugh at seeing over 1 million damage per shot when playing the sniper as it should always be played.The price seems fair for what it is, but ideally you should try to get it at a 50% discount. I also recommend a 4-pack if you think at least two people you know would enjoy playing the game with you, even if you only play with one of them at a time."
