,Recommended,248820,8352913,"Posted: 27 December, 2013",all,rob,"This is one of the best indie game I've played.  It's a relief too because I'm tired of 9/10 indie games being god damn puzzle platformers.  Seriously it's getting ridiculous.RoR is, according to the devs, an ""action platformer/adventure game with randomized elements.""  Your goal is to make it through 5 stages, wading through hundreds, thousands of enemies in the meantime.  When you start stage one the timer begins and counts up.  The timer carries over across levels and the game's difficulty increases non-stop as the timer reaches certain checkpoints.What helps you survive the hordes of enemies as you journey to each stage's teleporter to reach the next stage are dozens and dozens of powerups, health boosts, and activated items that make you pretty much a one man army yourself.PROS:The game is brutally difficult and progression is extremely rewarding.  The items are really fun, varied, and make you FEEL powerful.  You'll eventually become basically the Terminator, but that power is balanced out by the fact that you'll be facing hundreds of enemies and you can die at almost any moment.The music is fantastic and is sometimes fast-paced, sometimes slow and eerie.  It always fits with the game's alien world settings perfectly.You'll be able to unlock tons of new characters and new powerups that aren't just cosmetically different; they offer cool changes to gameplay that keep RoR fresh.And you have to try local and online co-op modes.  The game begs to be played with friends.CONS:The menus are a bit wonky sometimes and gamepad support for the menus is lacking.  At times you can navigate menus with the gamepad and other times you'll have to set it down to use the mouse for a sec.  Kind of weird and hopefully it'll eventually get smoothed out.Also, using a gamepad (I use a PS3 controller via MotionInJoy) is almost a necessity; using the keyboard is a bit awkward and will give you carpal tunnel syndrome within 5 minutes.  That said, your character's responsiveness to the gamepad is sometimes lacking.  When changing directions to fire at enemies behind you, you have to change directions a bit slow and deliberately, otherwise the game won't read the direction change and you'll just fire in the direction you were originally facing.  This can be a big problem, especially at higher difficulties when you can die quickly.  But once you get acclimated to it you can work around it.  Still, needs to be addressed.OVERALL:Totally recommend.  Buy it, even at full price."
