,Recommended,248820,7789747,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,Erics,"A solid action rogue-like that reminds you how kickstarter can really help quality games succeed.Plays like a side-scrolling shoot-em-up. You are dropped into a semi-random level that throws hordes of enemies at you as you level up, buy items with the cash you gain from killing enemies, and ultimately searching for a portal to advance to the next level.A neat feature is that the game's difficulty ramps up the longer you play, so you need to balance the time you spend on each level with how much you need to collect items and level up.The developer of the game has claimed that they are still 100% supporting the game, and already have many planned features for the future. Considering the current state of the game (really fun), and even more great stuff heading for it, I'd definitely say this is worth your money."
,Recommended,248820,8169635,"Posted: 21 December, 2013",all,Peanut,"This game is insanely fun and perfect for short or single playing sessions (although sometimes it can drag on if you know what you're doing and purposefully replaying levels).It features a very simple control scheme that is easy to handle but changing your playstyle based on your chosen character and the randomised item pickups (which are absolutely essential in order for you to survive) grants the game a lot of depth and replayability.The game is built to be played more than once (naturally; being touted as a rogue-like) with no explanation on how things work after being dumped into the first level except for the control scheme briefly being displayed and your current (very simple) objective. You're supposed to figure the rest of it out yourself.You learn how everything works rather quickly (thanks to the intuitive nature of the game and the simple control scheme) and the effects and threats of various enemies, you also unlock new characters and items to access as you progress with achievements in the game, giving you more reason to replay the game over simply beating your previous your score or mauling another 2000 aliens before dying.The difficulty of the game increases as time passes, so a sense of urgency is given to the player to continue forward and finish a level instead of wasting time, which may seem harsh to newer players to begin with but when you start to get into the flow of the game it feels natural and forces you to be on the move constantly even while not under immediate threat.Last of all the game features an incredible soundtrack that essentially makes half of the game by itself, it is truly spectacular and great example to all developers that audio for a game (particularly the soundtrack) should never be neglected."
