,Recommended,248820,13982715,"Posted: 14 January, 2015",all,Bakaloid.,"Genre: Hectic 2-D action platformer with roguelike RPG elementsGame Time: 4~10+ hours""The game is set in the distant future, where space transportation is common. Space trains carry passengers and goods all across space. A particular space train, however, had some very special cargo. Through a series of unfortunate events, this space train gets shot out of orbit and crash lands on a mysterious planet.. with one survivor.""-From Risk of Rain WikiaAn Interesting NoteInitially the title ""Risk of Rain"" implies different origins. It could imply the pain from its roguelike elements or the loose plot where the cargo, which is potentially dangerous, falling onto the planet like meteor showers. However according to an e-mail response from the developers, ""…it came around as an idiom of chance, because the game was very chance-based… It also coincides with the chests 'raining' from the sky, and our hometown Seattle.""Initial impressionRoguelike games has never been my cup of tea when it comes to entertainment. Sure they're alot cheaper and are easier to purchase, but that's pretty much the only reason why I would risk spending even dollar on. Risk of Rain (as RoR) on the contrary made me thirst for more. I saw myself clicking the ""play"" button repeatedly and despite the length of the game, I had a great time shooting down critters and getting plummeted by Magma Worms.""Visuals!""Assuming you have viewed the trailer, RoR is without doubt, pixel-based. This is the point where a surprising amount of customers have their opinion's divided. I personally agree with what Totalbiscuit said that there could have been more done with the visuals, but since the game can't get more visually neat than now, I see this as an reasonable compromise. We're talking about an Indie game here after all.In summary, the visuals are clean and are easily understandable. The colors don't feel dull especially when each one of the maps are distinct. The effects are flashy, and although you'll get to the point where everything goes fubar, the game is fair from what you expect. Oh, but them infinitely spawning Wandering Vagrants in the last level, they were a massive pain in the butt. Even if you're picky in-terms of graphics, getting frustrated and confused from how you died, or how you're being hurt will be the least of your concerns.Mechanics(Contents)Now in RoR you have plentiful numbers of passive items as well as interesting active items and drones you'll find throughout each randomized level. However what makes RoR so addictive aside from it's procedurally generated worlds, are its twelve characters that create a basis of your gameplay.You begin with the Commando, the standard shoot & dodge character, to the Acrid, a beast equipped with poison potentially lethal to even the hulking bosses of the game. Of course you will quickly create a preference on each character, but you'll be inclined to come back to for a refreshing gameplay, especially for Co-Op. The point that has to emphasized here is that to say the characters in this game define RoR, isn't even the slightest understatement. Experiment, and enjoy the variety. Most of all, have fun taking down hoards of those monsters. Before you get utterly destroyed, though.What the game offersOver a hundred items that are categorized with rarity, aside from a few, there are no two items that have the same effects.Interesting artifacts that mostly make the game hard, but more interesting. For example the Hive Cluster artifact makes the randomized loot, choosable. The Origin artifact on the otherhand, spawns Imps and a Imp boss every 10 minutes.Very limited, but unique maps that provide flavor and decreases boredem to the game."
