,Recommended,248820,7907343,"Posted: 3 December, 2013",all,jc helmet,"Risk of Rain is a horribly morbid game.Don’t get me wrong. I say this in the nicest possible way. This rogue-like shooter essentially drops you into a random area, with nothing but your arsenal and item boxes to prevent you from being mauled alive by reptilians, jellyfish, and tiny little Shadow of the Colossus looking things.Your task in every level you’re placed in is to “find the teleporter”. On finding the teleporter, a prompt appears, giving you 90 seconds to ‘stay alive’. Funnily enough, that is quite literally the entire premise of a game, not just an objective to be fulfilled.Risk of Rain uses a particularly cool mechanic in its gameplay - the longer you play, the more powerful the enemy spawns become. And that’s where the morbidity of it lies - your fate doesn’t lie in being speared to death by a boss, or failing to save the princess, you’re quite literally overcome in a battle you’re pretty much destined to lose.Nonetheless, you continue anyway - as with all rogue-likes, one run is going to be absolute dogshit, where as the other is going to be the luckiest you’ve ever been, like, ever. (Insert your own appropriate “luckiest day” metaphor).But with the timer mechanic, save scumming can’t save you - for the uninitiated, using numerous save files to generate the best possible outcome - because you’re playing in short, ten to twenty minute chunks. It’s a neat little trick to keep you hoping that you’ll get the run that’ll grant you just ten more seconds before you’re finally overcome by aliens.The game’s graphics are delightfully lo-res, with a beautiful muted palette. The weird scenery of wherever the hell you are is alluringly bleak, ranging from a dried up salt lake, or a weird mushroom forest. The feeling of desolation really sets in from the get-go, as the environments are so large, and your character is so small.Admittedly, the size of your player character does become a bit annoying when trying to track where you are in the midst of a gunfight, and losing friends in co-op mode is an annoyingly frequent occurrence, but on the other hand, it really does give an incredibly foreboding feel regardless.Much like Dark Souls, a similarly “morbid” game, a lot of the game’s lore is told in the logs and the item descriptions. The monster’s designs especially are surprisingly well detailed, to the point of unsettling in some cases. Although no amount of interesting detail will make me hate the fireball things any less - the game even lists the enemy that most kills you as your “nemesis” in the stats, and I think I’ve given away what my “nemesis” is.Risk of Rain is a game that’s quite literally about conquering the odds stacked against you. And even when you do manage it, it’s ready to deliver a sucker punch that you never even saw coming - hence why I call it morbid. This is how rogue-likes should be made.9/10"
