,Recommended,248820,7789580,"Posted: 27 November, 2013",all,Divisor,"This game is ♥♥♥♥ing solid. It's challenging, fast-paced, incredibly addictive, and an awesome way to kill time. It plays like any standard action platformer—arrow keys to move, Z X C V to use abilities (unless you're playing with a controller, which I do), and revolves around careful positioning between you and your enemies as well as knowing the right time to chain your attacks together to be as effective as possible. At first this is easy; the starter class ""Commando"" is very good at maintaining distance from monsters, but after enough time has passed the game gets exceedingly difficult, to the point where it is nigh impossible if you aren't prepared.You'll be spending most of your time scouring your environment for item upgrades, killing monsters and picking up cash along the way in order to purchase them. Each upgrade is fairly unique from each other—some will regenerate your health more quickly, some give you a chance to freeze, knock back, or incite fear in any enemies you attack, and others will even cause your abilities to explode on impact. Not to mention the fact that you can find small drones to assist you along the way, whether they heal you periodically or help shoot stuff. While some upgrades might not be so useful on their own, with enough time you can stock up on dozens at once and completely wreck♥♥♥♥♥♥because you're so beefed up.Now, since this is a roguelike, there are such features as permadeath, random world generation, and chance. Of course, dying is by no means the end of the game, and in fact it's almost necessary to unlock any upgrades or characters you've received as a reward for completing achievements, but at the same time, survival is one of the most enjoyable parts of the game. I can't tell you how good it feels to watch a wave of giant♥♥♥♥♥monsters charging you only to completely wreck them because you have a significant arsenal at your disposal and you're smart enough to know how to use it.The random world generation and chance go hand in hand, though, and if you've played a roguelike before, you should be expecting that going in. Since the layout of the world and the monsters and items that populate it are all randomized, it is entirely possible that your world either doesn't have very many items in it, or the ones that it -does- have aren't the best. It can also be mildly frustrating to be going after a specific achievement only to find that you can't get it because your world doesn't have the right stuff in it. For example, there's an achievement that requires you to pass 4 shrines in a row (shrines offer you a chance at getting upgrades), and if the world you're in simply doesn't have 4 shrines, you're♥♥♥♥♥♥outta luck. Restart, try again, and cross your fingers. There's a handful of other similar instances in the game, but it certainly doesn't bog down the game as a whole. Random or procedural generation makes up almost half of the roguelike genre entirely.Difficulty is also one of the main reasons I enjoy this game so much. There's a timer on the HUD that tells you what difficulty you're currently on, starting at Very Easy and going up I think 8 levels from there. Over time, the timer ticks up and up and the game gets harder and harder. At first, I didn't like this idea because I felt that if I wasn't playing fast enough, the game would simply get too hard and I'd have no chance at survival. But that's the point. Play efficiently, think quickly, and the game rewards you continuously everytime you overcome a boss or mob of monsters. Once you start to get a feel for how the game progresses, you'll find that the game's difficulty scales pretty evenly with how often you're picking up upgrades. You'll only feel overwhelmed by the sheer number and force of your enemies if you lag behind or don't utilize the tools at your disposal correctly. And let me note real quick that I've only gotten to the hardest difficulty once by sort of cheating at the game, abusing a specific area in the world to stay mostly safe from harm. If I had strayed from that ""cheat"" for more than ten seconds, I would be dead. This game does not ♥♥♥♥ around if you make it far enough. It will keep coming at you and hammering you until you're dead and there's nothing you can do except survive for as long as possible. It's ♥♥♥♥ing awesome.---Entirely unrelated from everything else, but I will note one more issue that applies to anybody who has a multiple-monitor setup and is using stuff like Nvidia Surround or AMD Eyefinity (I don't, so I can't speak with 100% accuracy here, I'm just telling you what I know). The way the game handles scaling and resolution is wonky, to say the least. It's basically stuck to a 16:9 aspect ratio and won't go any smaller. You can't change the size of the window in windowed mode and if your resolution is bigger than 1920x1080, it will stretch to fit across all of your monitors and will be basically unplayable. If you have multiple monitors on your setup, you -can- still play, but it'll take some googling to find a workaround to make the game display properly. I recommend doing some research before you go and buy the game if this applies to you. Other than that, great ♥♥♥♥ing game."
,Recommended,248820,7890658,"Posted: 2 December, 2013",all,Alice,"An unusual breed of platformer roguelike that has cut away elements of the MOBA genre and absorbed them into its fleshy exterior to create a hideously enjoyable game. Much like in a MOBA you are racing an inevitable snowball of difficulty. As the game slowly increases the amount of variety of monsters spawning in your game the longer you survive. You survive through a combination of leveling up and acquiring items. Acquiring items is both random and a pick and mix. And aiming for certain builds adds additional depth to the game. All of the equipable items can stack for additional effect, with a few exceptions to prevent you from attaining god mode too easily. ( It can be done, but it takes a lot of dead bosses. )The game is also oozing replayability with challenges and achievements which unlock new items for you to find. 10 totally unique classes, 9 of which have unique challenges to unlock them. And a bonus score attack mode which appears before the final level that allows you to reroll through the maps from stage one again but with the monster spawn difficulty set to scale to infinity, how high can you go and survive? Bring an umbrella though, it might rain."
