,Recommended,248820,24370743,"Posted: 17 July, 2016",all,Burribro,"Risk of Rain: The Ideal RoguelikeTo start, I call this game the ""ideal roguelike"" because unlike many other games in the genre, Risk of Rain relies far more on your personal skill & knowledge rather than how lucky you get. How well you do in this game isn't about getting lucky and rolling some amazing item on the first stage that'll let you easily blow through otherwise annoyingly difficult areas (looking at you, Binding of Isaac) - instead, how well your runs go in Risk of Rain focus almost entirely on how well you know your character's abilities and the enemies you fight, as well as knowing how to properly pick your fights so your health isn't melted in seconds. Even with the best items in the game, you can easily still get wiped by getting cocky with crowds of enemies. This game is brutally difficult and expects a lot from the player, but it never once feels unfair or improperly balanced - every death could have been avoided with some more skill and it becomes a learning experience. I personally find that this game hits that skill > luck chord of a good roguelike perfectly, and dare I say it's the absolute best game I've played in the genre.To sum it up, Risk of Rain is an immensely fun and addictive game that has eaten over 100 hours of my life despite the average run typically lasting only 40 - 90 minutes.  The wide variety of characters encourages learning various interesting playstyles while randomized levels, enemies, bosses, item drops, and the added thrill of game-changing artifacts keep things feeling fresh and fun. Like frosting on a cake, the amazing soundtrack from Chris Christodoulou tops the experience off perfectly and makes Risk of Rain a satisfying game both audibly and visually. It is simply an amazing game that I'd recommend to just about anyone. I do wish it still received content updates, but the devs are busy enough with university already.Note: The multiplayer component has steadily gotten better over time and is fairly reliable these days, although you do have to connect to a host by IP rather than through the Steam network so it can get iffy if you don't know how to forward ports. It can easily support a large amount of people playing at once (5+), but watch out for network instability issues."
,Recommended,248820,16769421,"Posted: 28 June, 2015",all,Ursula,"Want something you won't get bored of anytime soon? Want a real challenge? This is a game for you, then, pal.The amount of variety and different scenarios you can get in this game makes this so much fun, especially when played in co-op mode. Its pace seems rather sluggish at first, but after some time the excitement levels reach the peak with the constantly rising difficulty. It's rather unforgiving, so it might not be suited for everyone, though.There is always something to do with unlockable items, characters and artifacts, and even after you catch 'em all it's still hella good. With many characters you can surely find someone for yourself. The loads of items you can get in the adventure make every run unique and make you decide the way you play it.The graphical style of the game is just beautiful, especially the backgrounds, tilesets and bigger enemies. And the music, holy magmaworms, it's a masterpiece. What you'll hear when you mercilessly decimate squads of Lemurians will stay in your head for a long time. The lore is shrouded in mystery, but for the curious it's also another neat thing to dig into.Summing up, Risk of Rain is an exceptionally well-made roguelike game. Even if there's no actual ""rain"", there is loads of ""risk"" in it. Definitely worth its price."
