,Recommended,248820,21066611,"Posted: 8 February, 2016",all,Oddbrother,"When it comes to surviving the hostile alien planet, time is against you. The name of the game in Risk of Rain is to speed your way through power and escape the dangers before they overwhelm you. Kill to adapt and grow stronger against the alien hordes before they outgrow and kill you, and hurry your way back to your drop-ship.The lore behind the game is pretty impressive and depressing at the same time. Your concern and hope for mercy is cast aside, knowing you were guilty of stealing everything from an uncharted planet. The one who caught wind of this decided to put your in your place. It's merely a moral summary of greed, consequences and evolution.There are various classes to unlock with each and every play-through, and every area is chosen in a random matter to hinder your progress. Eventually, though, when you find all the secrets within each and every area, you can gain an even bigger advantage or challenge yourself even further within every starting play-through. So the replay value can grow over time as long as long as you're curious and adventurous enough to explore every nook and cranny.Graphics are deliberately primitive, but performance is good enough even for a 2009-based computer. The old, rusty look of the wastelands and the survivors that dwell in it, with various creatures that glow, surprise and potentially shock the players with mini-bosses and special item drops. It would suck to walk these dull and hazardous worlds. But the struggle lies in the hands of the player. Your knowledge of each and every area in the game can also be advantageous depending on your monitor size and display resolution.Unfortunately, because of permanent deaths within every play-through, your time to think before you act may end up getting you killed before you make it to the end in one go. Once you've died enough times before learning everything and then finally beating the game, it can be satisfying. But only if you're patient and persistent enough to adapt."
