,Recommended,248820,12496548,"Posted: 14 October, 2014",all,High Power,"It's a turn-based strategy game. And, yes, Risk Of Rain can look seriously boring to the casual bystander, but for the person at the helm of the game every turn can lead to a weighty decision, giving the player a certain feeling of power that few, if any, games match.Almost half-way through this review, and I’ve yet to mention gameplay. Maybe that’s a tacit criticism in itself. It’s not that Risk Of Rain's gameplay is substandard – far from it – but it’s always firmly in the service of its overarching narrative. Consequently, the game is heavily punctuated by cut scenes – some brief, some quite long. Cut scenes become engrossing, and it’s joy to see them bleed seamlessly into the furious action.Can't wait for Risk Of Rain 2: Over The Hill. 10/10"
,Not Recommended,248820,19137712,"Posted: 17 November, 2015",all,Wicky Le Sinner,"Now, let me start by saying this game can be enjoyed, and if you like rogue-like games like Binding of Isaac or Spelunky, you'll more then likely enjoy this game... However it does has it's faults.The biggest issue I have with it is the way it handles difficulty. Now while I feel like the time based system in place,  where the longer you play, the harder it gets, is good on paper, in play it just proves to be more annoying. The game discourages level exploration considering these levels are huge, but have nothing in them, save for the teleporter and the chests/shops/alters, but the way the levels are generated make it so you HAVE to explore a level, and sometimes do it twice if you want any items. Some levels in this game practically force you to go a certain way each time you play through them, espicially in the Water Level, where you have to almost always go from right to left, get up to the surface, and find the teleporter.The Levels in this game really start feeling same-y, and soon, boring, and saddly, the combat follows this. This game likes to swarm you with enemies, which you may have seen in the trailers. However, the trailer is misleading in the fact that you are very unlikely to get this many items unless you basically go back to the first level of the run, and do everything all over again, keeping your past items and difficulty. This means you'll often be running away, turning to chip away at one monster's HP, occasionally all with the few skills that have pierce or AOE, rince, and repeat. This gets old very quickly and if that wasn't bad enough, considering how slowly you kill enemies, espicially without drones which again are random spawns, it causes things to become more and more difficult for you. The enemies health also grows with difficulty, as well as the spawn rate, making the problem become worse and worse with time.Now that wouldn't be so bad... if it wasn't for two things. The fact that to progress from level to level, you have to kill every single enemy, and this game revolves around kiting enemies.  The former brings out the issue of the player not being at fault for the game forcing you to waste time. Usually by the time the teleporter is ready, the player is ready to leave, maybe still has to kill the boss, but there's nothing left that they care for. However, with this game design choice, it goes against the games nature of Risk Vs Reward. At that point, you either need to accept the wasted time, and then money because going from level to level turns your money into a very miniscule amount of EXP, which is terrible in comparison to the Items that give your run a winning chance.Now, for kiting enemies... this just leads into HORRIBLE character design. Each character has it's own unique set of abilities, but over half of them aren't designed well enough for the game's play style. Take the Sniper for example. His specialty is taking out bosses, which, yes, he can do exceptionally well. What he can't do however is handle the horde of enemies on his tail thanks to the fact he only has one half decent escaping move, the Backflip, which is the opposite of the Commando's Combat roll, where you dive in the opposite direction you're facing. Characters like these make me wonder how pollished this game was. It really gives the illusion of choice, because only about 3 or 4 characters are actually worth using if you want to get anywhere.In the end, this game really fell short of expectations, and doesn't do a good job of making me feel like a death was my fault, unless I just up and kill myself out of sheer boredom or overly difficult enemies. This game is best enjoyed when you have people to play it with, and saddly the game still falls short in that department, given the fact that you can't host games without a seperate program like Hamachi or Evolve."
