76561198133573511,Recommended,248820,9933421,"Posted: 25 April, 2014",all,ZombieX22,"A heads up, there is only one life per playthrough.  You die = you start over.As far as I can tell, the levels themselves are built semi-randomish, but it's usually not that hard to find your way around after a little practice.  The first and second levels are always the same area (not same map), with the 3rd level (assuming you get there) apparently having a chance to be one of two, and so on.There are 3 difficulties.  Drizzle, Rainstorm, and Monsoon.  You cannot unlock item and monster logs on drizzle, but everything else can be done there.  All this basically does is decide how fast the game ramps up.  It starts at about the same place, but on higher difficulties it gets more difficult faster.  The game's in-game difficulty starts at very easy with the words ""Very Easy"" next to a timer and an experience bar.  As the timer ticks away, the bar gets more experience and eventually the difficulty levels up.  It caps out at ""AHAHAHAHAHA"" (approximately spelled right).  The higher the difficulty in-game, the more health and damage and sheer numbers enemies have, and the stronger the enemy types that show up.  Realistically though?  It gets ridiculous as soon as the first difficulty level up occurs.The whole point of the game is to get to the teleporter in each level, activate it, wait for 99 seconds, and then kill all enemies in the level.  99 seconds is basically how long it will take before enemies stop respawning.  When you activate a teleporter, a boss enemy is guaranteed to show up, but whatever happens at any other point in time varies by difficulty and time elapsed.  As far as I can tell, the level one boss is a colossus and the level 2 boss is a magma wurm.  I am not sure if this is set or not, but the 4 times I've beaten level one and the 2 times I've gotten to the level 2 teleporter it's been true.  The colossus is just a giant @#$# regular minion that does 4 times the damage, while the magma wurm is the hard to keep track of looping through the environment kind of boss.  I've also seen an ancient wisp as a random spawn, which basically summoned columns of fire to mess with me.  :)   Once you've killed all enemies after the 99 seconds has passed, you can reactivate the teleporter to go to the next level.  The game has a fixed number of levels, although the order apparently varies randomly (I haven't gotten far enough to truly verify this), with a fixed final level and final boss.As difficulty goes, I have one problem with the game.  And that is that it really is a ton of luck.  Enemy damage and health amounts increase at a rate significantly faster than your health and damage amounts.  The difference has to be made up by in game items, which you have to get by killing enemies and spending the coins they drop (they also drop experience to level you up a little) to open chests / use shrines.  Chests cost a fixed amount, and some of them have items on display with your one time choice of one of three, but shrines are truly random.  Shrines have a chance of giving you absolutely nothing for your hard earned money, or worse.  The flipside of that is that chests are single use while shrines are multi-use, albeit at a higher price each attempt.  There are also some shrines where you can pay health, which is..... kind of severely risky but has higher rewards possible.Never the less, a good thing about items, assuming you get enough to keep up, is that every single one of them is stackable and has a practical use.  None of them are bs items you hate to receive.  And there are dozens of different kinds, all of them unique.  A successful run will usually see you getting hundreds of items.The enemy variety is also fantastic.  There are about 2 - dozen kinds of basic enemy, and more than a quarter of them have a boss version.  In addition, there are some bosses like the magma worm without a basic enemy :).  And almost every enemy is deadly.  There are also ""elite"" versions of enemies with elemental auras and such that cause you quite a bit of mischief.  Especially the overloading versions of bosses, which I have seen one of on Monsoon difficulty.The controls are basic.  You have 4 abilities assigned to 4 buttons, you have the 4 directional movements, you have a jump button, you have a button to activate stuff, and you have a button to use your ""use"" item.  One problem with the controls is that you have to hold ""up"" down continuously to grab onto a ladder, and this is finicky enough to cause some serious issues at certain points in time.  Jumping also has to be done very exactly in certain areas or you miss very easily.Multiplayer wise, the game has up to 4 player co-op.  The game becomes significantly easier in co-op.  I know this because I personally controlled two characters simultaneously (Jack can do that because he plays too much Guitar Hero), and one of them got to level 8 and the other got to level 12 before they both died.  This was one of the two runs where I almost beat the second level, and it was the significantly easier of the two.The only real problem with multiplayer is that they did not include any kind of matchmaking.  Or lobbies.  AT ALL.  You have to either play locally, with the 2nd and up person(s) using other control devices, or have someone host a server themselves.  And heads up.  There are noticeable possible security risks to hosting a server if you don't trust the other persons.  Which basically means.......... it's very hard to get in an actual co-op game here.  Which means that even though the game feels built for co-op difficulty scaling wise, the lack of any matchmaking whatsoever makes it very very hard for you to get into a game and requires extraordinary planning ahead of time honestly to do it safely.  So ...... the multiplayer kind of sucks.Overall, the only real problem other than no matchmaking I have had is that all of the unlocks, including the character unlocks that are supposed to be the replayability factor, come from doing things like beating the game 5 times, or beating a really hard enemy or something on level 4, etc.  I think the easiest is to beat level 3?  And some of the better items, the ones that make your playthroughs a lot easier, have hard unlock conditions in themselves.Overall, I would recommend the game at it's current sale price.  It's 3.39 right now, which I believe is totally worth it if you like ""rogue-like platformers"".  That being said, I would not believe it to be worth $10.Overall , I say 6/10 at the sale price."
