76561198010287273,Not Recommended,248820,28957898,Posted: 2 January,all,Kinetic Waffle,"So, I bought a four pack of this game, and I'm *utterly* disappointed.First up, the multiplayer is port forwarding nonsense or hamachi business. You know what other games do that? Age of Empires 2. Not the new one, the *old* AoE 2. HoMM3. Things from an age of gaming ago. This is antiquated multiplayer that is completely garbage, and frankly just lazy on the dev's part. Literally says online coop, and is on steam, but no... you've gotta screw around with this stupid nonsense to even get it working in this day and age.Then, the multiplayer. Oh, the multiplayer...There's this little thing in RoR that involves framerates- they can differ from person to person when you have a few hundred enemies on screen at once all pulling crazy pixel attacks everywhere that makes a computer choke up a bit. But if in multiplayer this happens at different levels, instead of time slowing down like in single player, the game just chokes this out as extreme levels of lag on the end of the person with the lower framerate.Sure, it'd be playable in theory- if you all have the exact same level of uber processor- but if one person has a janky computer, or even if you all do and view different screens at once because you're not in the exact same place? You're totally screwed, and everyone will die in a reflex perfect game,This is an amazing single player game, but selling this as a co-op experience with a four player pack to buy as if it's something you can enjoy online with your friends is a joke. I'd say this is probably the least functional multiplayer game in my library, level with No Man's Sky for how enjoyable the online experience is.You're close to making something perfect here, Hoopoo, but my god... one of the elements of this games advertisement I found most appealing was the biggest letdown, and you have some pretty serious work still to do on the online elements of RoR, given you made co-op experience three years ago."
,Not Recommended,248820,32496147,Posted: 16 June,all,TenSpaces,"Before I start: I want to recommend this game but the stability issues in this game can't go unnoticed. I've beaten the game twice in multiplayer and crashed both times while loading the credits, erasing all progress in those runs. While it is viable to go into the game data file and edit values to compensate for lost progress, the game should be able to save character progress throughout the run in order to prevent this sort of mishap.Moving on, the actual content of the game is great. The character selection is nice and there's much to unlock and accomplish. I've spent a few hours in singleplayer and multiplayer each trying to get artifacts and achievements. There's a decent variety of characters with a range of abilities. Item unlocks are based on character achievements, so there's a lot to unlock and many in-game achievements to hunt.Level design is good as well. Can't really complain here other than about how you might have to venture across the map to clean up enemies after the teleporter fight.Multiplayer is easy enough to setup if you can port-forward. As stated earlier, the game has some bugs with multiplayer, but it's fine for the most part.TLDR: RoR is definitely worth picking up if it's on sale or you don't mind the risk of crashing. It's a great game held back by some bugs. So much to do in the game and it's a fun game to play with friends."
