,Not Recommended,248820,20634870,"Posted: 19 January, 2016",all,Dreiszen,"This game is what it says it is- an arena-based roguelite platformer-shooter. Its parts don't really come together.The game has really stylish presentation and hints at a deeper story than ""space wizard blows up cargo ship"", but it really clashes with obvious VIDEOGAMES elements like everything being on cooldowns and enemies spawning in plain sight as a timer counts down and the difficulty meter goes up. You spawn into a room and dudes also start to spawn. Nothing is explained to you, except that you have to find a teleporter. The fact that it doesn't play or look like a plot-driven experience makes it bothersome that lore tomes are dropping in the middle of gunfights, but trying to enjoy the story and atmosphere they're presenting is muddled by it being pushed off to the side as arenas to kill lizardmen in.The gameplay flow isn't great either. Keyboard controls use the arrow keys, with abilities mapped to Z/X/C/V. Enemies are too difficult (read: have far too many HP) to be reasonably taken on in a stand-up gunfight and spawn faster than you can kill them off, so it seems like you should get to the clean-cut goal the game presents you and move on, but once you defeat the boss you still have to kill everything else in the level before you can leave. (For scale: your starting attack does ~5-6 damage for two hits and fires about three times a second. The first enemy you'll encounter has 100 HP.) There are flying enemies, but you can only shoot left or right, and even though they apparently have the least HP of any enemy, that just means they only have a little more than half health after a hit from the starting character's most powerful ability. The first boss I encountered is just a large version of this enemy that moves towards you and tries to sit on you and kill through contact damage, making it identical to its smaller versions save that its sprite is too large to be jumped over and it has in excess of 5000 HP. The evasive roll gives you i-frames, but using it with good enough timing to avoid incoming attacks moves you so far away that you can't use it to hold your ground, and most actual attacks are easily avoided by jumping anyway. Everything costs money and progressively gets more expensive, but you don't carry any over between levels. Altogether, the result isn't a horrible experience, just a tedious and grindy one. It's usually not so terribly unfair that I blamed the game for my losses. It's just that I don't lose because I get tired after fighting the same teleporting elite enemy for six minutes and alf-f4 out instead of killing the other 59.I avoided this game for some time. A significant warning sign is that this game is published by the developers of Starbound, another procedurally generated sidescroller that also has no sense of design and no idea how to put its pieces together, but a friend convinced me to get it for co-op. An advance warning: one of you will need to host, and that means one of you will need to port forward. Odds are that you either have already done this or can do it easily, but the point is that the game has no matchmaking or dedicated servers, nor does it have integrated multiplayer to ease the host-and-play process.If you like microscopic pixel art and ""hard games"" that hype up how often you die then I guess this is a fine choice, but the gameplay didn't click for me. I picked it up on sale for $2.50, so I don't feel super ripped off, but I wouldn't do it again."
