76561197983044014,Not Recommended,248820,9071671,"Posted: 12 February, 2014",all,Vaporwave Skeleton,"Risk of Rain stands triumphant as one of the worst videogames of all time.A control scheme that makes you realize maybe life isn't worth after all.A game engine designed for the fantastic, bright, and crisp resolution display of a Gameboy color. I'm still wiping away the tears of laughter from checking out 1x scale on a 1980x1080 monitor.An absolute beacon of light, a true monumental achievement in broken multiplayer as well. Risk of Rain does away with such cumbersome and needless options like LAN to opt for a much smoother, completly well realized local multiplayer all on the same screen. Because it wasn't enough that Risk of Rain wants to give you suicidal tendancies with its control scheme, it wants to spread the sorrow to all those you cherish and hold dear. My friend and I sat dumbfounded, looking at the game screen, as it casually insists that the second player also use the keyboard...It hurts just recalling the memory.And the cherry on top of it all - in their ever growing desire to appear cool, hip, retro, etc. the masterminds behind Chucklefish decided to give the actual online multiplayer a real blast from the past. For the first time in over a decade - since the ages of long gone gems like Age of Empires 1&2, Quake 1/2, UT99, etc. Chucklefish listened to what gamers wanted and loe and behold, we all shouted in one unanimous roar: ""We want antiquiqated manual IP address inputs! We want the game to arbitrarily select closed ports for connections!""I tip my fedora to the guys at Chucklefish. Way to make a statement."
