,Recommended,248820,21831694,"Posted: 14 March, 2016",all,Turtle OS 10,"""You die in a hilarious pose"" - Risk of Rain, on your death.Risk of Rain is a roguelike platformer that escalates in difficulty the longer you play. You play as the only survivor of a cargo ship crash on a hostile planet, hoping to survive long enough to escape. Standing in your way are lizardmen, giant crabs, living flames, and all sorts of other monsters. On your side, you have your gun and your wits.That's not quite true. You also have the contents of the crashed cargo ship scattered across the planet. Every area comes with chests you can spend money to open. These chests contain items that can give you extra health, the ability to deal critical hits, and other effects to even the odds against the endless waves of enemies that will stop at nothing to murder you.The core gameplay is simple. You start somewhere in a semirandomly generated area. Your goal is to find the teleporter that will take you to the next area. Kill the monsters that spawn to gain money and experience. Leveling up increases your stats, but money allows you to open the chests and operate the shrines that are scattered around the map for items, as well as activate drones to aid you im combat. When you activate the teleporter, you are given a countdown where you must stay alive, as the boss of the area and even more enemies spawn around you. When the countdown is over, enemies stop spawning, but you still have to kill every single one left before you can move on to the next area. When you do, all your money is converted to experience, so there's no rushing the next map for chests right out of the gate. You have to survive through five areas before you get the chance to enter the final map and face the final boss, but you can continue looping back through the five areas as many times as you want (or survive through, at least).The items you receive are random. Sometimes you run into machines that allow you to choose one of three, or ones that spin a roulette that stops on your cue, but for the most part, you aren't given much choice in what you pick up to help you. It may be the experimental drug that increases your attack speed, or the ukulele that adds a chain lightning effect to some of your attacks. Other items are activated manually, stopping time or granting you a shield of invincibility, with a cooldown between uses. As is standard for more modern roguelikes, there are persistent unlocks for completing certain tasks, increasing your item pool for future runs.The big draw of the game is the fact that the game gets more difficult the longer a run gets. Indicated by a dificulty meter that ranges from 'Very Easy' to 'HAHAHAHA', more and stronger enemies spawn the higher the difficulty gets. Even if you've filled the meter by 40 minutes, the difficulty still increases beyond that. At the higher difficulties, even bosses spawn on their own, without the prompt of a teleporter activation.Enemies also come in elite versions. Marked by a noticeable color change, these elite enemies have added effects, like increased health or explosive attacks, and gain more as the difficulty rises, like shooting homing missiles, healing nearby enemies, or teleporting directly to where you are.There is also a difficulty you can choose at the start of the game: Drizzle, Rainstorm, or Monsoon. Depending on the mode you choose, you may start with shorter or longer teleporter countdowns, along with slower or faster difficulty scaling, and minor adjustments to enemies. Of course, Monsoon rewards you for playing on a higher difficulty with increased chances of unlocking cool stuff, whereas Drizzle prevents you from unlocking anything besides items and doesn't even record high scores.Anything you kill outside of Drizzle mode has a chance to drop a monster log, which gives insight into the backstory of the game and the survivor's thoughts as they fight their way through the planet. Meanwhile, every item you've picked up can be viewed in the Item Log, with details of their effects and a little letter attached to each one. You did crash on a cargo ship, after all! Reading the Item Logs gives you a peek into where the items were intended to go, often with a little dark humor.You're given 12 characters to unlock on your runs through various methods. Every character comes with a set of four skills, which range from invincibility-granting combat rolls to just swinging dual pickaxes around like madman. Every character favors a different style of play, like the Huntress who excels at kiting, or the close-quarters Loader.When playing on Rainstorm or above, the maps can be generated with a hidden area and a puzzle to unlock Artifacts. These Artifacts can be activated when you choose your character, changing the way the game works. There is one unique Artifact per map.Find Honor in the Desolate Forest and face enemies that are all Elite!Bind yourself to Kin in the Dried Lake and be swarmed with armies of only a single type of monster!Fall victim to a Distortion in Damp Caverns and lock yourself out of a random skill every minute!Face your enemies' Spite in the Sky Meadow and watch them all drop bombs on death!Become as fragile as Glass in the Ancient Valley, dealing five times the damage with only one-tenth of your health!Find a mysterious Enigma in the Sunken Tomb, locking you to an activated item with a random effect every activation!Gain the power of Sacrifice in the Magma Barracks, making enemy kills the only way to get item drops!Take Command in the Hive Cluster and choose the items that drop!Fill yourself with Spirit in the Temple of the Elders, making everything run faster the lower they are on health!And if you can beat the game with all of them active at once, you will be rewarded with Origin, a sinister Artifact that gains the attention of the teleporting Imps that will invade periodically to kill you.Final rating: 120/120 seconds, kill remaining enemies!"
