,Recommended,248820,9266394,"Posted: 26 February, 2014",all,freshly poured lean,"It's hard to get bored with this game. All the characters have their own special tactics that are unique and take some time to hone. I always have a great time testing my luck on a shrine, or going for one more item, or all the other risks you will end up making along your playthrough that can drastically affect your end result, especially early-game.I really enjoy the multiplayer aspect, even though there are some things that still need to be tweaked for it to be a more enjoyable experience, such as how when someone dies in a previous level, they stay at the same experience level they died at. This causes a lot of issues, but that's the point of the game; death is the ultimate foe, and you need to do all it takes to ensure your survivability.The achievements range from♥♥♥♥♥♥easy to rock-hard in terms of difficulty, and anyone who gets 100% in this game is an absolute monster. Gameplay is always the same core concept, but the difficulty increases in staggering amounts quickly. Once you think you're unstoppable on Normal mode, go into Monsoon and you'll go right back to feeling like you are garbage. While there is always some randomness that affects how any run will go, a large majority of the time, death is your fault. It makes you want to go back in and use your four skills more effectively to dodge the hits at the right times, and put out massive damage.The pixel art, while a bit too common for indie games, is quite pretty. Visuals are impressive, and I always enjoy seeing how artists keep pushing what they can do with the craft.The music is so amazing and fits every stage it is played in perfectly. It puts you into a certain kind of  trance, while you try to desperately dodge all the elites that have just spawned in front of you, and you need to survive for 15 seconds more...I would not hesitate to buy the OST for this game.Definitely pick this up. Updates are coming out for minor bug fixes, new elements to gameplay are being added, and it's easy to just pick up and play for however much time you have, whether it's a few minutes or a few hours."
