,Recommended,248820,17797332,"Posted: 30 August, 2015",all,WarlordGandhi,"Intriguing, mysterious, and intense; words I’m surprised to find myself using to describe the pixel art styled Risk of Rain.  Mind, I might be over impressed by a bit since my tastes tend to lie in games containing HD explosions, but I’ve got respect for a game with this depth of detail on multiple levels.  Side scrolling roguelike Indies don’t tend to keep my attention for long, let alone so thoroughly and engagingly.  Panic, pace, power, and other words to compliment that alliteration will decide whether you thrive on the bounty of fallen enemies or fall to the overwhelming strength of your opposition.The gameplay elements held within are a maddeningly delightful conglomeration of luck and skill, with different ways to set up each game uniquely and provide a new experience.  Most of the characters and items you will come to know and love need to be unlocked through various tasks.  In light of its position as one of the hardest games I’ve ever played, Risk of Rain does let you start off slow.  Each game can be set with one of the three base difficulties: drizzle, rainstorm, and monsoon.  After starting any round, the base difficulty will slowly increase every subsequent minute starting from ‘Very Easy’ and escalating to ‘HAHAHAHA’, producing more powerful and numerous enemies.  Playing for the first time on drizzle is akin to riding a bike for the first time; if the bike’s handles were actually arms actively trying to punch you right where the sun don’t shine.  Also, the bike is slowly growing more arms specifically to hold you still.  That is to say, it’ll be even harder than you think at first while still being fun, and by the time you hop on your hell cycle that travels just under the speed of light and is comprised entirely of the pure essence of your own doom,  you’ll be ready from slowly working up to that point.You aren’t totally on your own on your hypothetical abuse bike, fortunately.  Scattered around the mysterious planet are various chests, shrines, and pods filled with tiny imps to slaughter for items.  With a wide array of functions performing defensively or offensively, passively or actively, you’ll spend most of your initial playthroughs learning what items do what and dying.  With no modifiers unlocked, luck will be a large factor in your survival as you learn maps and their variants, what gives items with varying luck/cost/frequency, and just how fast some enemies can make you weep with frustration.  Better yet, weep with your friends in up to four-player cooperative play!  Also make sure you’re distributing items properly, or doom your allies into utter defenselessness.  Items can range from almost-useless-but-fun to actually-useful-because-LASERSPEWPEW, with things like barbed wire, to damage one close by enemy at a time, or the ceremonial dagger, to cause enemies to fire heat seeking unholy bolts at the opposition.  Conveniently for you (inconveniently for the characters), you’re stranded on a mysterious planet after being shot down in a space train carrying a large amount of special cargo, so there is no shortage in number or variety of relics and munitions to fight with.What really got me with Risk of Rain was the lore behind everything.  Normally I just hop in and play a game with little concern for why I’m running from point A to point B obliterating everything in between, but the endings each character receive on beating the game caught my attention.  Without spoiling anything, even just the couple lines of text provided to conclude a character’s experience provides a secondary perspective, wrapping everything up in an eerie package.  The enemies in game are fun to fight, appear appropriately otherworldly, and vary from map to map, but the art and descriptions in the item and monster log paint a creepy picture of the twisted nightmare the survivor(s) face.  Wrecked on an unfamiliar planet, alone, with only supplies to scavenge, one can only imagine how disheartening it would be to see these malevolent creatures in endless attack.  A mask constantly erupting in flame, focusing extreme heat over long distances.  Floating, teleporting beings with a single red eye always locked on theirs, slashing with razor sharp talons.  Beings seemingly made out of light towering overhead, materializing to deliver crushing blows that shake the very ground on which you stand.Even the items you depend on for survival imply long term consequences even if you survive.  Take the jar of souls; upon use, it creates ghosts of all the enemies on screen that fight on your side.  Neat!  What’s the description?  “The recording only contains wailing and screaming.”  Jeez man, that’s freakin’ dark.  The ceremonial dagger I mentioned earlier?  “Finally found the heretic.  Foolish boy, thinking he could save his sister.  With the knife returned, we can continue our rituals.  Ah…  That should please Her.”  Holy crap, what am I even using?  It makes you wonder what it’s like to do what it takes to survive, only to find out that victory only brings living with the results of shooting yourself full of Soldier’s Syringes just so you can attack faster until the drugs likely do you in anyway.  Heck, even considering all of this made me hear the soundtrack itself differently; it sounded more suspenseful, alien, and all around captivating…Visions of potentially endless horror and scarring aside, everything about Risk of Rain bundles into one amazing struggle.  I didn’t even mention the various artifacts one can find and different map variants to provide new elements such as Glass Cannon, where you do 500% damage, but also have only 10% health.  Different modifications can shift a game more towards skill, luck, or just how dead you wanna be in the fastest possible way.  For the most fun, in my opinion, grab a friend, skip right along into almost certain doom, and make dominate the very concept of death and conquest.------------------View more gaming, anime, and art media atAniUMagazine.com-----------------"
76561198035671172,Recommended,248820,17802104,"Posted: 30 August, 2015",all,Jormundly,"I purchased this game on a whim. When a game is on sale for less than five dollars it is difficult to talk yourself out of purchasing it. This might just seem like every other roguelike pixel art game that crawled forth from the bowels of uncreative game design...but this one is different. This game actually gives you the feeling that you're lost on a distant planet because you don't know what to do.One of the more attractive parts of the game is how skill based the gameplay can be. Sure, if you're lucky with item drops and can manage to purchase enough to make yourself an aoe wood chipper the game becomes fairly easy. But it takes a lot of time as the amount of enemies spawning increases almost as much as their power. This makes it much more efficient to be better. If you can use the character you are playing efficiently you can beat this game in anywhere from 30 minutes to two hours. This brings about the main reason you play the game, the more times you beat the game, the more enemies you defeat, and the more creatively they are destroyed, the more you are rewarded. The ways you unlock items and characters are almost as satisfying as the unlockables themselves, with requirements ranging from beating the game to aquiring all of the food themed items in one run through.The characters are shining beacon in this games portfolio of awesome. Each one is completely different in feel from the last. This totally reinvigorates the game with every unlock, as the game feels completely different with some characters requiring twitch reflexes to survive, and others leaning more towards skillful combos to be successful. The bottom line is that each character feels different, has a distinct and colorful personality, and is well balanced with none seemingly overtly overpowered.If I had one bad thing to say about this game it would come in the form of the multiplayer, although you don't need to port forward to play online it is unnecessarily complicated, making this a better game to be played on LAN or just hot seat. Besides that multiplayer is very satisfying and becomes a grudging competitive co-op experience since the items are not shared. You of course want all the sweet swag to mow through enemies, but you also want your partner to be helpful in the late game, so it becomes an interesting balancing act of greed and charity.To wrap up this gushing session of my love for this terribly underappreciated game, I just want to say at least put this on your wish list. This is something that I could have completely missed out on and never been the wiser. But after playing this game I can honestly say that I will never stop playing this game. It may not be my most played, I may not ever unlock everything, but I can say that I will always come back to this game when I'm looking for a good time."
