76561198010052915,Recommended,248820,19225130,"Posted: 22 November, 2015",all,Shai Hulud,Epic Video Game
,Recommended,248820,12320895,"Posted: 1 October, 2014",all,Stavi_Deluxe,"Risk of Rain is a fun little title that can often be ludicrously addictive. Speaking as someone who does not usually enjoy sidescrollers of any variety i was surprised to find myself playing this game for hours at a time, it really does nail the 'one more game' feeling.Risk of Rain is at it's most enjoyable on it's normal dificulty setting but unless you're playing co-op or are a skilled gamer, do not expect to see far past the third or fourth level. With that being said easy difficulty allows gamers of any skill an excellent chance to see all the game has to offer, though do not expect a cake walk. Contrary to what the game says unlocks DO persist across difficulties, at least the useful ones like extra characters and rarer items.While tackling the subject of difficulty i must address one of the games major flaws; it's FAR too reliant on luck. The game has random item and deployables in chests to augment your character, MANY of these are Useless or Overpowered and due top their total randomness and ability to stack, one finds oneself at the mercy of the RNG. The run in which i beat the game, for example, was only acheived by finding a huge swarm of drones and a combination of items that made them supremely overpowered, to the point that i barely felt any challenge. Arguably the random loot adds to the addictive factor but one can often feel cheated.Luckily said items add immeasurably to the experience, many changing your playstyle on the fly. The same goes for the deployables, although because of the RNG loot one can go entire runs without finding a single one.  As i previously mentioned some items/deployables are barely worth picking up and others are very powerful, however realising how well the 'ceremonial dagger' and 'will o' wisp' are going to work together, or any of the other combinations you discover, is still a treat. Also worth mentioning that some items show barely any benefit if they stack up and others become absolute god-killers when multiplied. You'll quickly get to know your favourites and test driving a new unlock is always a treat.To discuss the items and deployables further i should mention that a good portion of them are unlocks. The feats required range from the simple to the darn near impossible and have a satisfying range in between.The controls are good but having played with a controller i would have preffered the abilities mapped to the face buttons. As i don't feel the shoulder buttons and triggers of the Xbox 360 pad offer the tightness of control that some of the abilites require. On another subjective note many of the characters are most effective when 'comboing' their powers,  if the face buttons were used it is my belief that it would feel more natural to do so.Some of the games mechanics and systems can sometimes feel a little off and some deaths will feel cheap or simply leave you flummoxed.  A couple of the cooldowns (of both abilities and deployables) can feel a little prohibitive. Both of these points are well illustrated with the 'Enforcer' character, his ability to block oncoming attacks does not always work as intended and can lead to cheap deaths, to compound this his shield barge attack, which can alleviate the former problem, is also on a harsh cooldown.The art and music are charming at their worst and fantastic at their best. One minor criticism is that some of the soundtrack loops are slightly too short and may get a little irritating.Can't speak for the multiplayer but judging by the quality of the rest of the package i'm sure it works well, if you're a Milquetoast Panty-waist that is :P.This is a solid recommend. :)"
