,Recommended,248820,10844925,"Posted: 26 June, 2014",all,Adventis,"Charming little indie title creatively named 'Risk of Rain' even though dire weather conditions will be the least likely of your concerns in-game. Much like its rouge-like indie brethren, 'The Binding of Isaac' & 'Rogue Legacy', Risk of Rain has the player trekking through randomly generated stages, looking for a way forward whilst searching for powerful items that, in hope, will make you broken enough to tackle the overwhelming odds the game throws at you.Make no mistake when I say that this game is HARD, as hard as any of the titles previously mentioned, but perhaps a bit more forgiving than both. There is always a clear sense of progression even though it is a rouge-like and the real draw of the game lies in its -class- system. The player is given the option of choosing between 10 different characters at the start of every playthrough, most of which are unlocked by meeting special conditions. There are tons of unlockables and each character has a highly unique, defined skillset and play style, which add endless flavor to the game because not only are you getting a different experience each time with the randomly generated stages; each run can also be worlds apart due to how each class plays out.Overall, a really great gem of a game and there's not much I have to say about it from a negative standpoint. It can be a little frustrating at the very start with nothing unlocked and only one character available, but it is only a matter of time before the game opens up and becomes far more enjoyable. The item buffs you can collect are all fairly ingenious and well thought-out but the game suffers a little from framerate issues in the final stages. Although that could be expected what with the -hundreds of missiles- probably flying around on your screen by then.  ;)A risk of rain?  Maybe not.A risk of losing track of time?  Most definitely."
,Recommended,248820,11178811,"Posted: 11 July, 2014",all,baby jesus,"Risk of Rain is an 'action rogue like platformer' where you explore a level to find an exit, fight some bosses, picking up powerups, while racing against a rising difficulty meter.One reason it took me so long to buy the game is because I hate games with timers in them.  Timers generally just add stress and frustration to games without any additional fun, and are a misguided fallback to the arcade days.  If you also feel this way, fear not.  The difficulty timer in this game doesn't work like that, it's more of a real-time representation of the standard difficulty curve of a roguelike.  It is quite possibly the only game with a timer which seems to work ok.  You don't fail if you run out of time, it just appears the difficulty stays maxed.  The game might still be better without it (why can't levels just get harder as you get further through the game, like every other game?) but it's not the fatal flaw I feared it would be.I also think the MMO inspired skill timers are not very intuitive to use, it would have been nicer like every other game where you just push buttons and things happen.The music is also great and if you are a sucker for good music like I am (check their videos for samples) it is worth the price of admission alone."
