,Recommended,248820,12333363,"Posted: 2 October, 2014",all,HelpComputer,"In risk of rain, you play as the sole survivor of a space-faring vessel that crash landed on a strange, alien planet, along with all it's goodies. I suppose maybe it was the space postal service, because that sh** ain't ever gettin' delivered now.In risk of rain (you'll feel the pain) Your goal on each map is to find the teleporter while taking out swarms of aliens hell-bent on murdering you, then activating the teleporter on the map, setting off a larger boss mob and even MORE aliens hell-bent on murdering you. You are required to Survive for X amount of time after you activate said teleporter as well as kill all the remaining aliens on the map the spawned endlessly and rapidly during said countdown.Along the way on your journey, you'll encounter several chests from your downed spaceship that you'll have to purchase and use to have any chance in hell of surviving. Items purchased have a wide variety of effects ranging from freezing time to making your character move faster, jump higher, attack faster, etc. Generally speaking, the more expensive the chest, the better the item quality.In addition to these special items your character has four abilities that have a cooldown/rotation before they can be used again. Each skill falls under a category: damage dealing, specialization, evasion, and/or crowd control. Using all of them to their fullest, as often as possible is going to be the key to your survival. along with the previous mentioned item gathering.As your current game playthrough progresses, the enemies become more and more difficult. There's a bar in the upper right corner of the screen. As time progresses, it fills more and more. The difficulty you play on controls where the difficult starts. Don't think you're terribad for deciding to start playing on ""Drizzle"" and/or ""Very Easy"", especially if you're new. I've seen games where the difficulty ramped up to ""I SEE YOU"" and ""HAHAHAHA""As you gain progress in what is sure to be many playthroughs, you may unlock additional classes to play as. Each class has its own unique playstyle and different ways of surviving on the planet. For example, while the commando, the default starting class is a sort of well-balanced jack of all trades, the sniper class focuses on damage dealing and can possibly kill bosses on a single hit of a fully charged, perfectly reloaded, droid scanned boss with their ""steady shot"" ability.In addition to unlocking new classes, you also unlock new items and/or artifacts that can be used to inject control (command artifact), Offense over Defense (Glass), or insane difficulty into your various play-throughs (Glass + Spite)The artwork and the ambiance for the game is phenomal. The alien landscape pefectly conveyed through pixel art. I have no complaints. It does the job well.The soundtrack is quite simply damned good and helps get you into the game and keeps you gripped. If you want to give it a listen outside of the game, I managed to find it on both spotify and youtube already. Give it a listen; you won't be disappointed.While the game officially states that it supports up to four player multiplayer I've seen folks hosting 10-player games easily. The fun, the difficulty and the triumph only multiply when you get multiple players on the field.When I first chanced upon Risk of Rain, I didn't really know what to expect. ♥♥♥♥♥'s /v/ video game forum, know for their love/hate relationship with video games and VERY hard judgement, had fallen in love with it seemingly instantly, and that usually means that the game in question is either bizarre but fun, or harder than hugh jackman's abs in an X-MEN movie.I found that I loved it immediately because the challenge I craved that simply isn't there in big-label mega-blockbuster titles was in risk of rain (on the plains on spain). With abundance.The game is remorseless. Unforgiving. Will make fun of you when you die, which you will do. Very often. You'll keep coming back for more though, because your un-named character on this un-named will continue to draw you in. You want answers and you want to get the hell off the planet alive.TL;DR: So damned hard, but so very very rewarding and so very fun."
