76561198098018169,Recommended,248820,12875241,"Posted: 10 November, 2014",all,FSLGS,"Harder, Better, Faster, Stronger: A Risk of Rain ReviewAs a fan of Roguelikes, I don't know why I hesitated for so long to purchase this game. Maybe it was because I already had bought 20 some games that I had yet to touch. Maybe the allure of difficulty kept me at an emotional distance. Or maybe I am in college and ten bucks will buy me food for a week. Nevertheless, during another ill-timed spending spree, I once again found myself on this very store page. And let me tell you, I didn't know what I was getting into.GAMEPLAY:Risk of Rain is an action platformer with roguelike elements, mostly pertaining to enemies and items, both what you get and how you get them. There are around 8 levels to be placed on, but each level has about two or three different builds, so they won't usually play exactly the same. Littering the planet are chests, which fell your ship, raining down onto the alien terrain. Yes, you were a delivery boy. A super cool space delivery boy. With a gun. Or a boomerang meat cleaver. Or a sword. Standard issue.Enemies spawn at random, and each level has their own set of enemies. On the beach, nice crabs and jelly fish; in the cluster, blobs and swines. The planet is unforgiving, and it wants you off it. Chests also spawn in random places, which can be purchased with gold dropped from killing enemies. It's a tried and true method, but here you're given a choice. You see, the difficulty scales to a cap the longer you play, so time management becomes a factor. Not an overly pressing one, but still very real. Do you farm an area for long enough to purchase all the chests, and shoot up three difficulties? Or do you bum rush the boss of each area, using the slight downtime post slaughter to buy whatever items are in the area? The choice is entirely yours, and you will face the consequences.The items purchased in chests are better labeled as ""modifiers."" You characters build won't change from its standard four attacks, but instead, amassing items will augment how much damage you dish out. The starting class, the Commando (Delivery Boy), has a double shot, a piercing shot, a dodge roll, and a five burst. But with a few items, suddenly your health starts regenerating faster, your shots start passively firing missles, you heal after every kill, and homing spirit orbs of death burst from the mutilated corpses of the fallen to seek out not yet corpses of the living. Doesn't that sound fun?Along with chest items, there are drones and artifacts. Drones are pay to wield bots that hover next to your character, and dish out ample damage over time. Once more, they proc your on attack effects, leading to some crazy shenanigans late game. Each one has their own attack patterns, but late in the game, they don't come cheap. Artifact, on the other hand, can be found hidden throughout the game, and allow you to mess with the core mechanics of the playthrough itself. With a few artifacts, suddenly you are dealing with only elite enemies of a single type that explode into frag grendades that only hurt you. While most of these artifacts allow for a new pace of the game or a challenge, some of them turn risk of rain into a race to god mode. Which is still fun, but loses its allure quickly.There is also multiplayer, but for the sake of its current status, I'm not going to spend a lot of time on it. It's fun, but rather glitchy right now. Give them time, they'll fix it, there is no reason to fear.SOUND:Risk of Rain has a fantastic tracklist done by Chris Christodoulou, with relaxed chiptune mixed with intense electric guitar, situation dependent. The eerie sounds of the pheramin mix perfectly with the dripping stalagmites of the Mushroom Caverns, until a giant worm of fire bursts from the ground, bringing with it an array of synths and snare hits. Not just the music, the sound effects are also spot on and well designed. Everything has its own little sound effects, from gashing to zapping to burning to exploding.GRAPHICS:The game goes with a very minimalistic look to it, with each character deigned bit by bit, with a more refined look in the logs. It's charming, never confusing, and sometimes, when the fights get crazy, and trust me, they will, both you and your computer will appreciate the sublime simplicity of each unit.VERDICT:This game is fun, and more importantly, it's best feature is its replayability. It took me about 40 hours to 100%, and only because the artifacts make achievement hunting a little too easy. Even after I got everything, I still come back to it and just jump into a game. It's quick, usually, fun, and with over a hundred items, there are never two similar playthroughs, sans those 100 minute games where you've got 500 items and are the Harbinger of Death. If you want a casual platforming rougelike, stop reading this review, and buy this game.PROS:+Replayability+A True Roguelike+Ten classes, Ten Artifacts, and over a Hundred Items+Wonderful music score and sound effects+Easy to learn, difficult to God Mode+Death Punishes, but you'll learn from it+Yahoo! You're a Deliveryboy!CONS:-Artifacts make the game often too easy. Luckily, you can turn them off-Allternatively, there are no daily/weekly challenges, which is something that would be well recieved-Multiplayer is not in a good spot right now-The game, at least for my friends and I, can't be minimized?-Once you've hit God Mode, you might see a slight dip in FPS-Addicting. Addiction is never a good thing, but it will happen to you with this game."
