,Recommended,248820,13297296,"Posted: 9 December, 2014",all,Hopesick,"With Risk of Rain, patience isn't only a virtue. It's a matter of survival. The game is certainly fun, but new players should bear in mind that when they first start playing, they will die quickly and often, even at the lowest difficulty setting.In Risk of Rain, you play as one of several spacefaring warriors who have crashed on a mysterious planet and must attempt to escape while fighting off hostile local wildlife. Although the basic premise and gameplay doesn't exactly break new ground, the game does introduce some unique mechanics that keep things interesting. Among these is the fact that the game's difficutly level starts off relatively low, and gradually increases the longer the player remains in the game, regardless of how far they've actually progressed. Each level has a randomly-generated teleporter that the player must find in order to progress to the next stage.  But simply running straight to it is a poor strategy since the player also needs to fight monsters and collect power-ups in order to become strong enough to face the later levels. This forces the player to manage their time well and creates a nice bit of tension that underlies the morally ambiguious nature of the game's story; the planet's background is slowly revealed to the player through a series of ""Monster Logs"" and it quickly becomes clear that the player is more of a genocidal invader than a lost astronaut (I know, moral ambiguity in an indie game? How absurd!).The big problem with Risk of Rain (one of many in a game that was written by two guys in a ♥♥♥♥ing basement) is that it only starts out with one playable character. And although the possibilty of unlocking more creates incentive to keep playing the game, the difficutly level makes unlocking more characters something of a grind, espcially when the starting character gets old pretty fast.If you do end up buying RoR, you'll probably want to beat the game at least once on the lowest difficutly setting before you try anthing tougher. You'll save yourself a great many broken keyboards and monitors in the process."
