76561198003420249,Recommended,248820,9027299,"Posted: 8 February, 2014",all,Handy,"Very good roguelike that answers the question ""If Binding of Issac was a platformer, what would it look like?"" Like Issac, this game takes ten or so playthroughs before you start to properly understand what you're doing, how it works, what progresison looks like etc. Which is not to say that it isn't fun until then -- it just won't be at the pure addiction level right off the bat.Additionally, while Binding of Issac comes with a lot of unlockable characters, all but one are essentially tweaks on a basic concept. I've only played the first two characters so far, but it that's any indication, in Risk of Rain, the difference in play style between the characters is enormous. I played the Enforcer once and went ""Wow, this is terrible."" I gave it another try understanding that it would be a departure and now I only want to play with Enforcer. Can't wait to see what else there is!The only small complaint I have is that the controller integration could be done a bit better, as you do need to click the mouse to start the game (I think). At the very least, it's not intuitive."
,Recommended,248820,9029681,"Posted: 9 February, 2014",all,whypick1,"Gameplay = great. Everything else = ...not so much.The bad: Crashes (often get fatal exceptions or process not terminating when quitting) and bugs (no audio; had to un/reinstall *every* C++ runtime once, now it's down to appearing ~every other boot), balance issues (Huntress is *RIDICULOUSLY* overpowered), interface (gamepad far and away best way to play this game...except you can't use it in any of the menus period), IP-based multiplayer (what is this, 1997?), consistency/clarity (mainly in regards to achievements).The good: ""Just one more time"" gameplay. Difficulty curve that seems steep at first, but with practice becomes very reasonable and manageable. Huge variety of items that offer great synergy with each other (great combo: ""always critical strike enemies at low health"" + ""heal on critical strikes"" + ""increased attack speed on critical strikes""). Wide variety of classes to suit individual playstyles (outside of Huntress being seriously OP). Really manages the ""carrot and the stick"" style of roguelike unlocking, outside of a few that are basically impossible without co-op (where we come back to the ""IP-based, seriously?"" thing).Hell of a game for a 3-person effort."
,Recommended,248820,11536190,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Fliss The Fluffy,"Risk of Rain is a game that takes the Roguelike genre seriously. I have not yet managed to complete a whole run of the game, but I can safely say already that it is definitely worth playing.Your goal is simple. In each level, find the teleporter while killing (or sometimes running from) everything that moves. While you move through each level, you will find enemies randomly spawning in front of and behind you and you have a choice. Kill them or run. Normally you would choose the former, but time is precious in this game.The more time you take, the harder the game gets. So while you may feel compelled to look through each level to get as many items as you possibly can, you may have to fight your instincts if you want to stay alive. This game is a bit like Spelunky in that regard. You do not have a strict time limit, but taking your time will make it a lot harder to win.The game features several characters with their own unique skills that you can use to get as far as possible, but in order to unlock any of them, you have to fulfil certain requirements, so it can be a bit tricky to beign with. But with perseverance, you will find that there are plenty of ways to make your characters a lot tougher than they look.After all, there are plenty of items you can find along your way, either locked in chests, dropped by bosses or obtained from various shrines (if you're lucky). These items provide a huge variety of different effects that can turn your character into a killing machine. However, you need gold to get them, so be prepared to earn your bonuses.All in all, it's a fantastic game. It can be extremely hard at times, but the satisfaction of being in command of a godly berserker which can tear down groups of large enemies in seconds is worth the effort."
,Recommended,248820,10352688,"Posted: 4 June, 2014",all,Jolly Roger,This game is the only indie game I've really gotten into.
76561198040457997,Recommended,248820,11540767,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Keemossi,"Awesome game.Uh, details. So, it's sort of platformer action roguelike. Your goal on every level is to reach the teleporter, activate it, survive for a while and kill the remaining enemies on the level. Every enemy you kill gives you experience, which increases your character's damage, durability, speed, and so on (a bit depending on what class you play). You also get currency you can use to open chests, buy items, or gamble items. Anyway, currency = usually items in one form or another.The thing is, the enemies get constantly stronger. The longer you take to finish a level, the stronger the enemies will be on the current level, and every following level. You need to find a good pace where your character is strong enough to progress, but not take too long and end up weak compared to the enemies.The game doesn't take too long to finish, I think 20 minutes is doable ( in real time, in game time I think the record is somewhere like 12 minutes - there are items that stop time and such). The first playthrough can take a good while though, since the game isn't exactly easy. You'll likely unlock at least a few classes on the way.Every class plays differently, like.. a lot differently. Although after a time the levels will start to repeat themselves, the classes and randomization of items will extend the gameplay value way beyond the initial playthrough.Don't know what more to say... awesome game, buy it, love it :p"
76561198070541530,Recommended,248820,11576144,"Posted: 6 August, 2014",all,Cherry Tomato,It was fun.
,Recommended,248820,11577985,"Posted: 6 August, 2014",all,OmniRemix,"This is an amazingly designed game. If you like roguelikes and/or pixel shooters, stop reading and buy this game.Risk of Rain is so, so well designed. The game feels organic, being completely foreign and impossibly difficult when you start playing, but becoming more familiar and easier as the game goes on; but not by virtue of leveling up or any kind of avatar strength. Instead, the player becomes more familiar with the level layouts, the monsters, the items, the bosses, and the characters themselves as they play, gaining a sense of skill along the way.This is the way roguelikes should feel. Hostile, mysterious, and dangerous. But as you die and die and die, you learn and grow as a player, carving a much easier path for yourself through the game.Not to mention that the art and music here are both top-notch and unique. If you're a fan of the pixel aesthetic, you'll love the look of the strange alien world.It's a no-brainer. Highly recommended. You gotta play this."
