,Recommended,248820,8660792,"Posted: 11 January, 2014",all,namnatulco,"Despite the ""permadeath"" mechanics this game advertizes, this game isn't frustrating at all. Perhaps most importantly this game doesn't use the typical platformer mechanic of ""touch enemy = damage"", which makes the gameplay much more varied. It's a lot of fun!"
,Recommended,248820,8661729,"Posted: 11 January, 2014",all,"Earth, the Green Knight","I can honestly say I love this game to itty tiny bits. It's got a good idea going- essentially a Two Dimensional Time Attack Binding of Issac, with multiple classes with entirely different movesets that synergize differently with the items you'll find along the way. It can get infuriatingly hard if you're not careful to either bulk up fast or move fast enough to beat the really difficult enemies, and some characters seem more focused on multiplayer capabilities than single-player fun, but there's very little wrong with this game.However, some of these wrong, or perhaps divisive is a better term for these, things can be a turn off. Very little is explained to you- some item descriptions are completely unhelpful in determining what the item actually does for you. Unlocking descriptions are on the whole very good at telling you what you need to do to unlock the next shiny object for helping your character survive the onslaught of the planets inhabitants, but some are incredibly vague. Character unlocking descriptions are the worst offenders here, perhaps to add to the challenge of finding that new class to play as.You also are given little instruction on some of the mechanics. Damage is slightly confusing to first consider, the system runs on the idea that you have a base damage value that can be considered the starting point for determining all of your attacks damage. Depending on the % value your skills have for that damage, you either are hitting harder or weaker than your actual basic damage. Skills don't have individual damage values, which would tell you if you do 10 damage or something similar, and so figuring out if you're going to be relying on something heavily for damage or not is a bit of guesswork and reading the damage numbers whenever you hit an enemy. The % system gives you a sense of what's going to hit some baddy the hardest, but gives next to no indication of how many hits an enemy will take.The last thing I consider to be a major flaw is the design with the wall tiles and drones in the game. In essence, drones are little companions that can help you survive by healing you or hurting your enemies, and they ussually do this quite well. The walling system in the game, however, makes things only have solid sides, say the floor you're standing on or the cieling above you, and completely passable center areas. This means that drones will often fly into the center of the platform you're standing on to try and shoot an enemy that's on a plane below you, and then innefectually shoot at a wall when you'd rather them try to actually shoot an enemy. This problem also extends to item drops, as some items and monster logs end up stuck in the wall with no possible way to retrieve them.Even so, considering the majority of the game was developed by a two man team, this game is stunning and wonderfully entertaining. Finding ways around the problems mentioned above aren't too strenuous, as the item list gives exacting instructions as to what each item does, adduming you've both unlocked it and found it in the game. The damage system may be confusing at first, but it quickly becomes intuitive within a few runs at the game. The real problems mentioned above are annoying when they happen, but only the drones flying into wall spaces actually happens often, as in several hours of play I've only had one or two things become stucking in walls, and they were usually just monster logs. I heartily reccomend this game to anyone who enjoys games similar to The Binding of Issac, and also those who enjoy a good sci-fi game.(P.S: I'm a fan of controllers for games like these. While I haven't played the game at all with the default Keyboard settings because of my rabid love of controllers, I assure you they are just as good and it's just a matter of personal preference.)"
