76561198025508545,Recommended,248820,12450622,"Posted: 11 October, 2014",all,Atheistic Monk,"Risk of Rain is another take on the much beloved rogue-like game genre. Those of you who enjoyed Binding of Isaac and Rogue Legacy will probably also enjoy this little gem.The graphics are 8-bit, not really that uncommon for an Indie game, but you can still feel the effort they put in them. They're not simply there for the reason a lot of hipster indie game developers use 8-bit graphics, i.e. for the sake of their pretentious artistic integrity. The graphics in this game are like this to convey the feeling of those old but gold and hard as heck games like Castlevania, Metroid and Cave Story. The art direction itself is also really well done. The different levels always give you a metroid-like feeling. They're beautiful, they make you wanna explore them, but at the same time they kind of frighten you, give you the feeling that at any time something bad could happen. And I know I'm repeating myself, but in the end it feels like a subtle hommage to Super Metroid and those kind of games, which in my case I can't have enough of.The game runs and controls smoothly, the only problem I have is that you always have to pause and then skip the opening animation when you're starting it up. Also the partial support of the gamepad really throws me off, because you can't select your characters with it or look at the items. Can't really say anything about the coop, because I haven't tried it yet, so I won't.The gameplay itself is also very well executed. You can play as ten different characters, which not only look, but also play differently. From the long-ranged, flexible, but not that much damage dealing Commando to the very close ranged Acrid, they all have their own perks and, of course, disadvantages. Most of them are unlocked if you do something special, so that you have a little motivation to play the game besides just finishing it. The action skills (four of them) you have in this game are almost always active skills, besides the items you pick up. Which brings me to the next point: items/passive skills. All over the map are containers with items that can boost your stats or even give you somewhat active skills. Those can be either that you heal faster outside of combat, have a better attack speed or even launch a mortar while attacking normally. And you can get a special item you can use actively, so you can escape certain dangerous situations. Besides the regular action skill (every character has one special to him) all of the action skills have a cooldown so you can't just go rampage on that poor planet, so a little strategy is needed when dealing with hordes of monsters. Last, but not least, you can change the difficulty from easy to hard if you're in need of a challenge. The further you come in a session, the harder the game gets. And you can collect hidden artifacts if you want to have a little fun while playing. They always grant you certain advantages and/or disadvantages, e.g. that enemies explode on their death or that you deal far more damage while also just having a fragment of your health. All in all it proves that it has a really tight gameplay.The music in this game also sort of gives me this feeling that only the Metroid series can give me. The feeling you're all alone on a big, dangerous planet. Beautiful, but highly dangerous. It also sounds kind of like the Metroid Prime series, I don't know if they got their inspiration from it, but it's always a plus in my book. It just fits in perfectly with the rest of the environment. The tracks themselves are mostly ambient tracks which compliment the landscape you're in, but in certain situations like boss fights they can also be very aggressive and alarming. All things considered it's a really great soundtrack.If you still don't know if I'd recommend this game, I do. It has really tight gameplay, looks pleasing to my eyes, has a wonderful soundtrack and high replayability. It's not often you find good rogue-like games like this, so definitely buy this gem of a game.TL:DR version: If you liked TBOI and Rogue Legacy, buy it, you cheapskate. It's only nine dollars."
,Recommended,248820,12593353,"Posted: 21 October, 2014",all,8BitSaint,"Compelling and surprisingly deep gameplay, with almost infinite replayability."
